-- Housing/Human Settlements meetings — Batch 8 of 8
-- 90 rows (meetings from Human Settlements committees 91 and 291)
-- Run after: supabase_housing_batch_7.sql (if applicable)

BEGIN;

INSERT INTO meetings
    (pmg_meeting_id, committee_name, committee_id, date, title,
     summary_clean, pmg_url, num_documents)
VALUES
    (36505, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-03-08', 'Engagement with Metropolitan Municipalities on Urban Settlements Development Grant, informal settlements upgrading, serviced sites and land invasions', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements engaged with the eThekwini Municipality, Nelson Mandela Bay Municipality, and Buffalo City Municipality on the Urban Settlements Development Grant, informal settlements, service sites and land invasions. This was part of the Committee’s theme this term to engage with metros on the use of grants and general matters relating to housing. The eThekwini Municipality informed the Committee that the city’s resilience had been tested as eThekwini through many flood storms with the most severe being in 2019. The climate change crisis has affected the city''s budget and planning efforts. Further, the lockdowns and economic shutdowns because of the Covid-19 pandemic have also harmed the functions of the city. The civil unrest of 2021 has had a devastating impact on the city''s development. The floods of 2022 which have not been experienced in about 100 years, have slowed the city’s ability to deliver social services to communities. The response of the city to these crises has been robust and efficient; this has ensured that services are delivered to communities. The delegation from the Nelson Mandela Bay Municipality (NMBM) stated it is embarking on formalising informal settlements. Land invasion is still a big issue in the NMBM. But a dedicated team is focused on assessing and responding to land invasions. In the 2023/24 financial year, plans are in place to ensure the land invasion is attended to at various stages. The current land invasion strategy includes using a unique number of shacks to control growth. The Municipality is in the process of developing a Security Plan with Safety and Security to protect the municipal land. There have also been communication strategies through cluster meetings with local leadership to ensure its collaboration. Buffalo City Metropolitan Municipality, like the other municipalities, proposed that amendments are required to the Prevention of Illegal Eviction from Unlawful Occupation of Land Act (PIE ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/36505/', 0),
    (36560, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-03-15', 'Department of Human Settlements Q2&3 2022/23 Performance', 'Video In a virtual meeting the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) reported a 62% target achievement in Quarter 2, which was a 4% increase from the first quarter, and 71% achievement in Quarter 3, a 9% increase from Quarter 2. Committee members were happy to see improvements in some areas but were concerned about the reoccurring issues in some provinces and municipalities. Members asked about permanent job creation; asbestos roofs and mud housing; grant reallocation and its impact on citizens; implementation plans to assist provinces and municipalities to avoid future unspent grants being taken away; project procurement challenges; blocked projects; lack of bulk infrastructure to housing projects; District Development Model deployment; issuing of title deeds; delayed invoice payments and acting staff in senior management positions in DHS.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/36560/', 0),
    (36604, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-03-22', 'Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority update on implementation of AGSA recommendations; Implementation of FLISP Programme, with Deputy Minister', 'Video In a virtual meeting, the Portfolio Committee was briefed by the Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA) on implementing the Auditor-General South Africa (AGSA) recommendations. The Committee also received a progress report on the implementation of the Finance Linked Individual Subsidy Programme (FLISP). The Deputy Minister, who attended the meeting, stated in her address that the first change to be made towards implementing FLISP is to rebrand the entity. Research carried out indicated that ordinary people had insufficient knowledge about the programme. The PPRA delivered a presentation which discussed progress made on implementing the AGSA’s recommendations with the focus being on material findings which resulted in a qualified audit opinion and also disclosing the status of the high vacancy rate and other Human Resource issues. One of the audit findings included the Inventories (Existence of Inventory Communication of Audit Findings 35). The PPRA explained to the Committee that one of the steps taken to resolve this finding was that the management in finance would perform inventory counts and invite AGSA as of 31 March 2023. The AGSA’s administrative findings include non-compliance with the recruitment policy during the appointment process as per the Communication of Audit Findings (COAF) 28 with 31 March as the timeline of completion. The Executive and Board of the PPRA approved appointments. Since the dismissal of the previous CEO, recruitment for the position has not yet commenced. An unfair dismissal dispute with the Commission for Conciliation Mediation and Arbitration (CCMA) has been set down for 25 April 2023. The Board of the PPRA agreed to update the Committee on the progress of the matter once it has commenced. The First Home Finance Programme has been developed by the Department of Human Settlements to enable sustainable and affordable first-time homeownership opportunities to South African citizens and legal permanent residents earnin', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/36604/', 0),
    (36812, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-05-03', 'DHS, NHBRC, HDA, SHRA, NHFC, PPRA & CSOS 2023/24 Annual Performance Plans; with Minister and Deputy Minister', 'The Portfolio Committee convened in Parliament to receive a briefing from the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) and its entities on their strategic and annual performance plans (APPs) for the 2023/24 financial year. The entities that were present were the National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC), Housing Development Agency (HDA), Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA), Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS), Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA), Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA), and the National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC). The Department’s medium term expenditure framework (MTEF) budget allocation for the 2023/24 financial year was R34.9 billion, of which R 23.5 billion would go to integrated human settlements planning and development, and R9.3 billion to informal settlements. In terms of the Human Settlements Development Grant, the nine provinces would receive an amount of R14.9 billion in 2023/24, which would increase to R15.1 billion in 2024/25, and to R15.8 billion in 2025/26. The HDA told the Committee that the targets in its 2023/24 corporate plan were informed by commitments made by the provincial Departments of Human Settlements and municipalities, and the requisite funding being transferred to the Agency. It was assumed that these commitments would not be withdrawn, or payments delayed, as this would impact service delivery on the ground. All funds transferred to the HDA would follow the Division of Revenue Act (DORA) initiated by the transferring officer before their release to the HDA. The NHBRC said it would focus on operationalising the approved organisational structure and filling all vacant positions. It was working towards implementing a digital complaints registration platform to simplify and speed up housing consumers'' dispute registration. For home builders, the entity intended to introduce a homebuilder grading system to reduce enrolment fees, inspect all subsidy-enrolled homes, and issue the fin', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/36812/', 0),
    (36860, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-05-09', 'Human Settlements Budget: Committee Report', 'Video Tabled Committee Reports The Committee on Human Settlements met on a virtual platform to discuss its draft report on Budget Vote 33 and the minutes of a previous meeting. After discussion, it was decided that the Members could read the minutes on their own, and rather meet next week to adopt them. This was done because of time constraints, and all were in favour of this proposal. The Committee was taken through the draft report. They noted several grammatical errors in the report. They suggested many amendments, among which it was stressed that six months was too long a period of time to wait to do effective oversight. It was proposed that this time period be revised. Members recommended that the National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC) and any relevant stakeholders needed to accept accountability and improve their performance management. It was also asked why R18 million had been spent over a month just to house flood-affected residents from Crystal Valley. One of the Members suggested that the goals not achieved in the previous year be noted, and that they had to be achieved in the new year. The draft report was subsequently adopted with the amendments.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/36860/', 0),
    (36954, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-05-17', 'Material irregularity and audit insight shared during BRRR: AGSA briefing; NT Policy to reallocate funds between provinces and metropolitan municipalities', 'Video AGSA: BRRR Presentation In a virtual meeting, the Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements received presentations from the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA) on the material irregularities and Budgetary Review Recommendation Report, as well as a presentation from National Treasury on the policy to reallocate funds from the various provinces among other issues. The AGSA indicated that the presentation was preceded by various discussions held by the entity on matters of the accountability ecosystem. The main purpose of the Proactive review was to understand the preparation and revision process of the updated five-year plans and final draft APPs, as well as the alignment to the Medium-Term Strategic Framework. Another purpose was to assess the completeness of relevant indicators relating to core functions and service delivery expectations of the citizens. The AGSA outlined some Material Irregularities and said the report on pervasive mismanagement of public funds without consequences and audit recommendations had not always received the required attention. The Committee raised concerns over the presentation and clarity-seeking questions. It questioned the powers extended to the Auditor-General, especially in dealing with the recommended Material Irregularities and the time frames so that the public could see the outcomes whilst the matter was still ongoing. Members were concerned about the processes involving consequence management and highlighted that the presentation did not provide clear and adequate information. The Committee Members asked for an explanation of the outcome of issuing certificates of debts, what it would mean in practical terms for the residents, and the impact on Accounting Officers. National Treasury presented the policy to reallocate funds from province to province or from metropolitan municipality to metropolitan municipality which would impact the reallocation to the Medium Term Strategic Framework (MTSF) targets monitoring to ensure ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/36954/', 0),
    (37042, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-05-24', 'Western Cape Department of Infrastructure response to oversight visit; DHS update Mawiga Ministerial Project and Mawiga Four Petitioners', 'Video During the virtual meeting, the Portfolio Committee received three presentations. The first dealt with the oversight visit by the Western Cape Department of Human Settlements in April, followed by a progress report on the Magiwa Ministerial project, where Phase One of 8 000 property transfers would commence on 1 June, and the situation involving four Magiwa petitioners. The Committee concluded its meeting with a report on the Department''s second and third quarter performances in 2022/23. Responding to the oversight visit report, the Committee raised several questions regarding the removal of asbestos in houses, the housing situation for disabled individuals, and concerns about the backlog of title deeds. The progress report on the Magiwa project dealt with the plans aimed at resolving the ownership and transfer of properties to 14 000 households residing in Ga-Rankuwa Units 7 and 8, Mabopane M, S, U and X, and Winterveld. Also, it focused on four Mawiga petitioners whose properties were illegally sold and transferred by officials in Tswane and the North West Housing Corporation. The Chairperson acknowledged that the Committee had not acted urgently in taking the illegal transfer of the petitioners'' properties to human rights lawyers. However, they were facilitating a private meeting with the office of the Public Protector to align their efforts while finalising the case. They were committed to expediting the process, and intended to meet with the Special Investigating Unit (SIU) regarding the case. They would urge the SIU to take up the matter to ensure a swift resolution.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37042/', 0),
    (37112, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-05-31', 'DHS Q4 2022/23 Performance; Northern Cape and North West Oversight Visit Report; with Ministry', 'Video Tabled Committee Reports The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met on the virtual platform to receive a briefing on the Quarter Four performance of the Department of Human Settlement. At the beginning of the meeting, the Committee discussed a recent oversight visit to the North West province. A few issues were identified from the visit; those included the unfair process which a female contractor, as well as a disabled contractor, had been subjected to, the lack of basic municipal services to some of the military veteran''s houses and the need to accelerate the digitalisation process of the housing beneficiaries list. In the Department’s interaction with the Committee, Members enquired about the appointment process for the new Policy and Legislative Review Team (POLERT), the implementation of the Auditor-General’s recommendations in the North West province, the state of contracts that were awarded to women, youth and persons with disabilities and the Department’s oversight over its entities. Members expressed concern about the Department’s unfinished houses, which remained unoccupied as the building materials on site were often stolen after they were not attended to for a long time. That would be a huge waste of money for the government. Members also expressed concern about the corrupt practice of Departmental officials moving up the housing allocation list and urged the Department to take action to curb that trend. Among other concerns which Members had raised, there were issues around the low quality of the houses that the Department built, the unqualified and ethically compromised housing inspectors, the informal settlement crisis in Khayelitsha, the Department’s slow response to MPs’ questions, the Department’s under-expenditures on goods and services and payment of capital, etc. Members suggested the Department establish a war room to provide additional assistance for the Free State Provincial Department as the situation in that province required imm', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37112/', 0),
    (37176, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-06-07', 'Adoption of Committee Minutes', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to deal with outstanding minutes. Tshwane''s failure to appear before the Committee for a briefing due to financial constraints raised concerns, prompting a proposal to retain their funds until engagement. The Committee proposed visiting Tshwane to investigate water-related challenges leading to serious health concerns, and to invite other committees that may be interested in joining in the visit. They also decided that Tshwane''s expenditure of the Urban Settlements Development Grant (USDG) over the past five years should be researched. The Committee adopted previous meeting minutes, except for 30 May, which required further amendment. A briefing on a submission call was given, and Members were reminded to prepare for their proposed overseas study visit.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37176/', 0),
    (37244, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-06-14', 'Cities of Johannesburg and Mangaung on utilisation of Urban Settlements Development Grant, informal settlements upgrading programme, serviced sites & plans to curb land invasions', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met in Parliament for a briefing by the City of Johannesburg and Mangaung on the utilisation of the Urban Settlements Development Grant, the informal settlements upgrading programme, serviced sites, and their plans to curb land invasions. The Committee was unhappy about the absence of senior officials from the Mangaung Metropolitan Municipality. It was critical of the explanation of the Tshwane metro that it did not have the money to travel, so the Committee would go there and conduct thorough oversight. The Committee raised a number of concerns relating to targets not being met and funds not being spent by the Johannesburg and Mangaung municipalities. It was also concerned about the "Mafia elements" destabilising housing projects, and asked about the plans to curb this and protect the surrounding communities. Members pointed out that many problems and instability in the municipalities were of a political, rather than administrative nature. The political leadership of these municipalities should be called to account to the Committee. The Committee lamented the fact that national and provincial teams had been sent to Mangaung to resolve its issues, but no improvement had been seen to date. It expressed disappointment over the non-payment of service providers, and delays in decision-making involving officials who allegedly paid contractors for work done only if they received a kickback of 10%. Members also questioned why budgets had not been passed in some areas, and whether this was due to multi-party coalitions. The issuing of title deeds remained an issue in many areas, and law enforcement did not adequately and timeously respond to land invasions within 48 hours, which gave the invaders rights when the government failed to act within a certain timeframe. Members expressed concerns about personnel in acting positions, as it seemed that they were appointed based on closing a vacancy, rather than on their capabilities, and', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37244/', 0),
    (37293, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-07-05', 'Update on SIU TRU Investigations; City of Tshwane utilisation of USD & ISUP Grants; DHS support to provinces affected by floods (with Deputy Minister)', 'Video The Special Investigating Unit (SIU) gave an update on its investigations into housing corruption in 5 provinces: Limpopo, Free State, Eastern Cape, Mpumalanga, and Gauteng. The SIU told the Committee that its investigations uncovered and indicated endemic corruption, maladministration, and malpractice in the DHS, as there is evidence of the abuse of emergency procurement which was mostly evident in the PPE procurement. It is important that as part of the PFMA amendment, the checks and balances in emergency procurement are tightened up. There has been an overlap between disaster management and COVID-related procurement, ignorance of procurement policies, general poor record management, and delays in handing over documents, but in the main, the fact that the Department did not get value for money shows that there is poor project management. The SIU said it is in the public interest that consequence management happens even though in many instances when officials see that investigations are happening and outcomes are incoming, they are quick to resign. The Committee expressed concern about the timelines in which the cases are concluded by the SIU and were gravely disappointed that the Department was neglecting its primary responsibility of doing checks and balances and monitoring projects to ensure that they are implemented fully and according to the law. The Committee also questioned the blacklisting process undertaken by the SIU, the Department, and National Treasury, expressing concern that the same companies that transgress against the state also get appointed by the state in other forms, whether as individuals or new companies. Members said the presentation spoke volumes about how the government is undermined by officials tasked to protect the citizens. The national department should monitor norms and standards because it gives directives on how things should happen, and the provinces and municipalities should be addressing issues of implementation from thos', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37293/', 0),
    (37387, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-08-30', 'Postponed: KwaZulu-Natal & Gauteng on MinMec 2022/23 Priorities and Budget Expenditure', 'In Parliament, the Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met for a briefing by the Gauteng and KwaZulu-Natal provinces on the Ministers and Members of Executive Council ( Minmec) priorities and budget expenditure for the 2022/23 financial year. It also considered outstanding Committee minutes and reports for adoption. Members were told that the delegation from KwaZulu-Natal was unable to attend the meeting physically as agreed, as their flight had mechanical issues, but the two provinces had been aware of the briefing that was set to take place. The Committee agreed that it would communicate to KZN that it strongly rejected their reasons for not appearing before the Committee. The Committee would reschedule the meeting,', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37387/', 0),
    (37439, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-09-06', 'Mpumalanga & Limpopo on MinMec 2022/23 Priorities and Budget Expenditure', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements was briefed by the Mpumalanga and Limpopo provinces on the Ministers and Members of Executive Council (MINMEC) priorities and budget expenditure for the 2022/23 financial year. The Committee heard that Mpumalanga had only two blocked projects in the 2023/24 financial year, which were situated mainly in the Govan Mbeki Local Municipality, due to a lack of bulk infrastructure and illegal land invasions. The province said it had not quantified or created a database of the number of mud houses in the province, and its eradication of asbestos programme had been allocated R50 million for the financial year. The Department indicated that some of the challenges related to disaster responses were because several of the reported houses could not be repaired as they were big structures, exceeding the size of a typical government low-cost house. Some houses were poorly built and did not conform to building standards, while others were mud houses and shacks which could not be repaired under the emergency housing grant conditions. The Department pointed out that residents would often report poorly maintained or incomplete houses as being disaster-affected. Limpopo Province reported that it had 161 blocked projects on its housing subsidy system due to non-performance by contractors, lapsed contracts, terminations, and balances still reflecting on projects. The Waterberg, Mopani and Sekhukhune districts'' townships were currently at advanced stages of proclamation, and would be prioritised in the 2024/25 financial year. The Department had appointed the Housing Development Agency to implement two main strategic programmes for eradicating asbestos roofs, and 1 500 roofs had been completed. The process of reviewing the informal settlement development strategy was currently underway across 81 informal settlements, affecting approximately 47 783 households. The province reported experiencing challenges with the availability of bulk infrastruct', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37439/', 0),
    (37494, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-09-13', 'KZN & Gauteng on MinMec 2022/23 Priorities and Budget Expenditure', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met in Parliament for a briefing on the Ministers and Members of Executive Council''s ( MinMec''s) priorities and budget expenditure for the 2022/23 financial year by the KwaZulu-Natal (KZN) and Gauteng provinces. KZN reported spending 91% of its budget for the 2022/23 financial year. There were 43 stalled human settlement projects across the province. It had spent 93% of its provincial emergency housing grant allocation amounting to R318.3m as at 31 March. Among the challenges resulting in district municipalities'' poor performance were issues related to land acquisition, spatial planning, and insufficient bulk infrastructure such as water, sanitation and electricity. The funds paid to municipalities for human settlements projects were used to pay Eskom, salaries and bad debts. Municipalities were also not enforcing bylaws to deal with land invasions, and the occupation of flood lines and non-developable areas had led to families being affected by flood disasters. The Gauteng Department of Human Settlements (DHS) reported on its progress in dealing with the construction of houses in blocked projects. The Committee heard that the houses affected by asbestos in Gauteng were in the old pre-1994 townships. The province had not yet committed funds to eradicating asbestos roofs, as it was awaiting feedback from the national DHS on a framework to guide the implementation approach. The province said it was not removing some mud houses, as some were strong and neatly built and were used by families for various reasons, such as storage. The Committee also heard that some families would not move into houses built by the Department, as they were often reluctant to relocate for sentimental reasons such as gravesites, or did not want to leave the houses they had built, even though their houses were inaccessible from the main roads. Members asked for clarity on socio-political issues in KZN, and whether these were masking a forum for crim', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37494/', 0),
    (37555, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-09-20', 'Free State and Western Cape on MINMEC 2022/23 Priorities and Budget Expenditure; with Deputy Minister', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements was briefed in Parliament by the Departments of Human Settlements in the Free State and Western Cape on the Ministers and Members of Executive Councils (MINMEC) priorities and budget expenditure for the 2023/24 financial year. The Deputy Minister said that the slow pace of issuing title deeds in all provinces remained a concern, while the removal of asbestos roofs required specialists, as it was not as simple as anticipated. The Committee heard that there has been instability within Free State Human Settlements, affecting the delivery of houses. The majority of provinces have eradicated mud houses and have done well on this, particularly in Kwa-Zulu Natal. The Department of Human Settlements indicated that it often intervened in capacity and procurement issues within the management team. The Free State Department of Human Settlements indicated to the Committee that its business plans were partially approved. The Department highlighted that it would experience a R3.1 billion budget cut proposed by the National Treasury, severely affecting all grants. But the Department would make a counter proposal. The Western Cape Department of Human Settlements pointed out to the Committee that it had undergone a few changes during its Change Management Process. The Department reported that it had approved critical posts for its branch, including a chief director for implementation and appointing at least two directors and some civil engineers. Members raised several questions and concerns, with some relating to the lack of financial performance information in the Western Cape’s presentation and a lack of targets. Concerns were also raised on how the respective departments spend conditional grants and more information on informal settlements upgrading was requested. The Committee also expressed disappointment at the high number of incomplete projects in the provinces and felt that this denied South African’s dignity, particularly in the', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37555/', 0),
    (37567, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-09-21', 'Tshwane Oversight Visit Report; Committee Report on DHS Q4 Performance', 'Video Tabled Committee Reports The Committee met to deal with in-house business such as considering and adopting a Committee oversight visit report to Tshwane and on the quarterly performance of the Department of Human Settlements. The Committee also dispensed of Committee meetings and the programme for the next term.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37567/', 0),
    (37650, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-10-11', 'Human Settlements Portfolio Audit outcomes & performance: AGSA & DPME input; DHS 2022/23 Annual Report; with Ministry', 'Video Human Settlements The Committee met with the Department of Planning, Monitoring and Evaluation (DPME) and the Auditor-General South Africa (AGSA) to discuss the audit outcomes and financial and non-financial performance of the human settlements portfolio. The AGSA said were no outstanding audits and all financial statements were submitted by 31 May 2023. The annual performance report showed that the portfolio achieved an average of 58%. With the entities, NDHS achieved 50% of its targets, NHBRS achieved 89%, HAD achieved 73%, PPRA achieved 31%, NHFC achieved 19%, SHRA achieved 58% and CSOS achieved 80%. The Committee asked about consequence management of the past financial years, progress to date and enforcement in place to deal with the repetitive findings. At what stage had the AG intervened and ensured that its findings had been reported to the Committee for assistance and to avoid repetitions? The DPME presented that in February 2023, the DHS launched the First Home Finance programme as a revamped version of the erstwhile Finance Linked Individual Subsidy Programme (FLISP) – a total of 5 811 households received financial assistance. 8 262 of the targeted 9 769 uninhabitable mud houses were eradicated in the rural provinces of Limpopo, Northwest and the Free State. The DPME developed a National Unblocking Programme - diagnostic evaluation of all blocked projects (3 445 projects identified) 925 of 1 873 targeted units delivered in 2022/23. The Committee asked if there was no need for internal monitoring units in the departments closer to where the programmes were. Why would the entities be de-linked from the Department when they were supposed to support the Department? The Department of Human Settlements then presented its 2022/23 Annual Report. It highlighted that its areas of improvement had included strengthened inter-sectoral collaboration for improved performance through the DDM, improved integrated planning, budgeting, monitoring and reporting, and imp', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37650/', 0),
    (37681, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-10-13', 'NHBRC, NHFC & SHRA 2022/23 Annual Reports; with Deputy Minister', 'Video National Housing Finance Corporation National Home Builders Registration Council Social Housing Regulatory Authority The Portfolio Committee convened on Zoom to receive a briefing by the Department of Human Settlements'' three entities on their audit outcomes for the 2022/23 financial year. All three entities -- the National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC), the National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC) and the Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA) -- had received an unqualified audit outcome. The Deputy Minister introduced the presentations by highlighting that 88% of the population now resided in formal dwellings, representing a significant improvement compared to the 1996 situation, when it had been 65%. This substantial increase underscored the progress achieved in housing provision over the years. The NHBRC said its key programmes were focused on professionalising its building inspectors, conducting lifestyle audits, expanding training programmes, safeguarding consumers through the warranty fund, and standardising the requirements countrywide for submissions to the NHBRC. The NHFC reported that it had successfully approved loans amounting to close to R1 billion, with disbursements totalling approximately R750 million. This demonstrated its commitment to providing financial support for housing. Its focus on enterprise development through procurement was evident, as it had disbursed R14.3 million to various beneficiaries, including 42 women-owned contractors and 15 youth-owned contractors. The SHRA highlighted challenges in the entity''s operating environment, particularly external factors such as the country''s economic crisis and the escalating cost of inflation, which affected the affordability of rentals and building costs for social housing units. It also mentioned issues with construction mafias causing disruptions on their sites, and contractors not adhering to the SHRA''s rules. Members suggested the entities should join forces to find ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37681/', 0),
    (37726, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-10-18', 'HDA, PPRA & CSOS 2022/23 Annual Reports; with Deputy Minister', 'Video Community Schemes Ombud Service Housing Development Agency Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority Three entities of the Department of Human Settlements -- the Housing Development Agency, the Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority and the Community Schemes Ombud Service -- briefed the Portfolio Committee in a virtual meeting on their 2022/23 audit outcomes. They highlighted the improvements that had been made, and the steps taken to respond to the audit outcomes, and expressed their commitment to continue their progress in the upcoming financial year. The Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA) audit outcomes drew criticism due to the identified shortcomings in its financial management and reporting. The entity acknowledged the challenges within the organisation, which emphasised the need for corrective action to enhance their financial practices. The CSOS received praise for the notable improvements in its audit outcomes, and for implementing effective strategies that had led to better financial governance and improved performance metrics. The Department of Human Settlements expressed a strong commitment to further enhance its performance in the following financial year, and assurances were made regarding implementing necessary steps and reforms to address shortcomings and ensure more robust financial management practices.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37726/', 0),
    (37793, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-10-25', 'Human Settlements Budget Review and Recommendation Report (BRRR)', '2023 Budget Review and Recommendation Report (BRRR) The Portfolio Committee considered and adopted its Budgetary Review and Recommendations Report (BRRR) for the Human Settlements portfolio having considered the annual performance reports of the Human Settlements portfolio.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37793/', 0),
    (37858, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-11-01', 'Ga-Rankuwa/Mabopane Petition; Breede Valley Municipality Petition', 'The Portfolio Committee met with the Department of Human Settlements and the Western Cape Government to discuss progress on the Garankuwa/Mabopane (MAWIGA) petition and the Breede Valley Municipality petition. The four MAWIGA petitioners, whose houses had been illegally sold, expressed dissatisfaction with the Department''s provisions for several reasons, such as the size of the properties allocated, and the level of redress arising from the fraudulent activity by municipal and provincial officials. Deadlines for the resolution of these matters were set. The Breede Valley Municipality''s petition aimed to resolve delays in the completion of housing projects in the area. During the discussion, it was asserted that political issues were hindering progress. The Department said it would collaborate with the Western Cape provincial government and the municipality to resolve the existing issues.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37858/', 0),
    (37922, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-11-08', 'Engagement with PPSA on Human Settlements matters; FS Department of Human Settlements on the Progress made on Recovery Plans', 'Video This meeting was held on a virtual platform to allow the Portfolio Committee to hear from the Office of the Public Protector on its progress in dealing with various complaints from beneficiaries of the Department of Human Settlements, and to be briefed by the Free State Department of Human Settlements on the progress made on their grants recovery plan. The Public Protector''s Office said most of the complaints received were related to issues regarding Reconstruction and Development Programme (RDP) housing. There were 82 cases currently under investigation. These were due to conduct failure, corruption, maladministration, and undue delays. Issues related to RDP housing included not being placed on waiting lists despite applying, finding their allocated housing being occupied by other families, and title deeds not correctly reflecting the rightful owner. Some RDP projects remained incomplete despite being started in 2012. Committee Members noted that the main issues reaching the Public Protector (PP) included the extreme delays and backlogs of applicants for housing, the delays in issuing title deeds, and the lack of continuity and urgency within the Office of the Public Protector. The PP presented statistics to substantiate the considerable strides that were being made to change the working environment within their Office, and to fast-track the processes that had been delayed. The Committee questioned the Public Protector on its choice of remedial actions, and the role it played in monitoring their implementation. The Free State Department of Human Settlements (DHS) provided a detailed and extensive presentation on their progress on the recovery of Human Settlements Development Grants. The Committee raised concern over the allocation of funds to particular department projects, rather than others. Members also asked about issues raised within the township development programme, and on the accountability of staff, contractors and criminals involved in maladministr', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37922/', 0),
    (37976, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-11-15', 'Eastern Cape & Northern Cape update on matters raised during Committee Oversight Visits', 'Video ATC231113: Report of the Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements on the oversight visit to the Western and the Eastern Cape Provinces, 8 November 2023. ATC230531: Report of the Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements on oversight visit to Northern Cape and North-West Provinces, 31 May 2023 The virtual meeting held by the Portfolio Committee of Human Settlements was to receive feedback on the progress made by the Northern Cape province, the North West province, and the Eastern Cape province on the recommendations given by the Committee during oversight visits. The issues raised by the Members were the slow progress on the issuance of title deeds, the slow progress in the termination of contracts with contractors, the eradication of asbestos, and the illegal occupation of unassigned housing. While the Northern Cape and the North West province reported some sufficient progress, the Eastern Cape, on the other hand, did not report exceptional progress and this feedback was met with disappointment from the Committee. The measures put in place to increase the issuance of title deeds included the inception of the “Title Deeds Fridays” initiative, which was implemented across provinces, and this resulted in numerous title deeds being issued. Members posed questions about the beneficiary list, and these were regarding the verification processes, the accessibility of such lists, and how allocation of housing occurred.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/37976/', 0),
    (38049, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-11-22', 'Postponed: Briefing by Operation Vulindlela on the progress made on Title Deeds', 'Video The briefing on Operation Vulindlela was postponed due to the non-availability of the Executive. The Committee dealt with its minutes. The Committee finalised its oversight visit to Stellenbosch.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38049/', 0),
    (38118, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-11-29', 'Department of Human Settlements Q2 2023/24 Performance; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Committee convened to receive an in-depth examination of the Department of Human Settlements'' performance during Quarter 2 of the 2023/24 financial year. Led by the Deputy Minister, the session covered various facets of the Department''s activities and addressed inquiries from Committee Members. Among the key points discussed were efforts to rehabilitate housing applicants facing financial constraints, ongoing consultations with banks, and a comprehensive three-year programme aimed at unblocking housing projects. The timeline for this initiative was clarified to span from the 2023/24 to the 2025/26 financial year. The Director of Human Resources addressed concerns about staff positions, and explained the need for reprioritisation due to budget fluctuations. Efforts to expedite the hiring process and address internal bottlenecks were emphasised. The meeting also delved into proactive measures the Department took to prevent the loss of housing, particularly through collaborations with commercial banks. The performance monitoring of designated groups, such as women-owned businesses, was highlighted, showcasing the Department''s commitment to fostering economic transformation. Challenges faced by a specific province, including budget cuts and political instability, were discussed with a focus on the criteria used for budget cuts, primarily based on performance measures. The impact of these cuts on the province, along with the Department''s efforts to manage funds effectively, formed a significant part of the deliberations. Insights into the Affordable Housing branch''s activities, including the issuance of title deeds and ongoing efforts to digitise beneficiary lists, were provided. However, concerns were raised regarding the progress in the digitisation process. The meeting concluded with the adoption of the previous minutes and discussions about upcoming meetings to address reports. Despite challenges and concerns raised, the Committee acknowledged the Departmen', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38118/', 0),
    (38226, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2023-12-08', 'Committee Report on DHS Quarterly Performance; Community Schemes Ombud Services Indaba Report; Committee Annual Activities Report', 'Video The Portfolio Committee met virtually to consider reports on the Department of Human Settlements'' second quarter performance, Committee participation in the Community Schemes Ombuds Service (CSOS) workshop, minutes of its previous meetings, and its draft programme for the first quarter of 2024. A Member highlighted the significance of the CSOS''s work, emphasising its critical role in empowering communities for future business ventures and socio-economic development. She pointed out that the CSOS addressed issues of redress and building capabilities within the broader community, contributing to better programme management and governance. She emphasised the complexities faced by the CSOS due to its involvement with diverse communities, both urban and rural. She suggested that the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) should closely collaborate with the CSOS to address these challenges. The Department reported achieving 86% of its targets in the second quarter. Members'' concerns were focused on the progress of the Informal Settlement Upgrading Partnership Grant (ISUPG), with a recommendation for the Department to present a strategy to overcome challenges preventing progress of the grant in the next quarter. They also highlighted challenges facing first-time home buyers, the backlog of title deeds, and the impact of budget cuts on the Department''s programmes.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38226/', 0),
    (38325, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-02-14', 'White Paper on Human Settlements; Accreditation Framework for Municipalities to Administer National Housing Programmes; with Minister', 'In Parliament, the Committee was briefed on a Draft White Paper for Human Settlements and on a revised framework for accrediting municipalities to administer national housing programmes. The Committee was told that the White Paper process could be finalised by the end of April 2024, following widespread consultation. Issues identified in the process included the needs of senior citizens and child-headed households; gender-based violence, especially in the case of women who co-owned houses with their spouses; and the repossession of houses by banks when owners lost their jobs and income. There was a proposal to increase the household income criterion for an RDP house to R5 000. There was a proposal to introduce a Human Settlement Ombud Another was to shift powers from the Housing Development Agency to the Minister of Human Settlements. Members were told this would address misalignments in control over state land which created problems in releasing land for the development of human settlements. The White Paper also dealt with expropriation of land for human settlement purposes. The focus would be on under-utilised land. It would bridge the spatial divide in urban areas so that the poor could be closer to economic opportunities. The new policy sought to overhaul funding for infrastructure. It aimed to streamline budgets and harmonise projects of different departments. Members were then briefed on a revised framework for accrediting municipalities to administer national housing projects. Municipalities would be accredited for implementing a programme or mixture of programmes relevant to their capacity and needs. In terms of the new guidelines, municipalities should demonstrate good governance through regular executive and council meetings, have senior management in place, have the human resources to administer housing programmes and have positive audit outcomes. The revised framework recognised secondary cities and intermediate city municipalities as important catalysts', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38325/', 0),
    (38379, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-02-21', 'Accreditation Framework for Municipalities to Administer National Housing Programmes; Implementation of AGSA findings: DHS & PPRA briefing', 'Video Report of the meeting to follow.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38379/', 0),
    (38446, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-02-28', 'Acquisition of state-owned land including Priority Development Areas and measures to curb land invasion/unlawful land occupation; DHS Q3 2023/24 Performance; with Deputy Minister', 'Video In a virtual meeting, the Portfolio Committee received briefings from the Housing Development Agency (HDA) and the Department of Human Settlements on the acquisition of state-owned land for housing development. The Department also briefed the Committee on its third quarter performance. Committee Members were pleased that the Department had achieved 88 percent of its targets. However, there were concerns about the provinces and municipalities'' underuse of grant monies. The Committee said it was concerned to learn that, as of 31 December 2023, just 45 percent of the Informal Settlements Upgrading Partnership Grant had been used. Although the Committee was in favour of the Department''s and National Treasury''s interventions - which included transferring R250 million from the Western Cape to Limpopo Province - it demanded that recovery plans be put into action as soon as possible to guarantee project completion and responsible use of funds. The Committee also applauded National Treasury''s intervention in sending letters about the stopping and reallocation of funds to metros that were not meeting their informal and urban settlements grant targets. After a briefing by the HDA, the Committee expressed concerns about access to land held by the Department of Public Works and Infrastructure (DPWI), particularly land in priority development areas that would be perfect for spatial transformation. The Committee said it appreciated the DPWI''s release of 2 500 hectares of land nationally, which now permitted municipalities and provinces to start development plans on those parcels. It did, however, voice alarm about certain areas, such as Limpopo, where allocations were small. The committee welcomed the announcement that the HDA had purchased three inner-city buildings in Johannesburg, Cape Town, and Kimberley for the purpose of redeveloping them for mixed housing. The Committee called for the urgent resolution of impediments to the ability of the HDA to access state-owned lan', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38446/', 0),
    (38515, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-03-06', 'Breede Valley & Ga Rankuwa/Mabopane Petitions Progress; Implementation of DDM in DHS', 'Video The Portfolio Committee met with the Department of Human Settlements and the Western Cape Government to discuss progress on the Ga Rankuwa/Mabopane (Mawiga) and the Breede Valley Municipality petition. The four Mawiga petitioners, whose houses had been illegally sold, expressed dissatisfaction with the Department''s provisions for several reasons, such as the size of the properties allocated. Deadlines for the resolution of these matters were set in the previous meeting, but there has been little to no progress. The Breede Valley Municipality''s petition aimed to resolve delays in the completion of housing projects in the area however since it had not, it was suggested that the Minister, as well as the Members of the Executive Council, pay a visit to the people of Breede Valley and immerse themselves within the community. A future date was set to allow the Department to present again with the Minister and MEC present. The Committee was briefed on the implementation of the District Development Model (DDM) in the Department.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38515/', 0),
    (38593, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-03-13', 'Ga-Rankuwa Petition; Third Quarter Committee Report; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee convened a virtual meeting with the national Department of Human Settlements, the North West and Gauteng Departments of Human Settlements, the North West Housing Corporation (NWHC) and the City of Tshwane (CoT), to be briefed on the progress of the case involving four Garankuwa/Mabopane (MAWIGA) petitioners. In 2018, the Public Protector published a report on an investigation into allegations of maladministration by the NWHC and the COT regarding improprieties in the sale and transfer of properties situated within the boundaries of the City of Tshwane by the Corporation. It had been discovered that three of the four petitioners’ properties, located in Mabopane and Ga-Rankuwa, had been illegally sold and transferred by officials in the COT and NWHC officials. The fourth petitioner already owned property in Ga-Rankuwa but had not been issued a title deed. The Committee then decided to assist the petitioners on humanitarian grounds and took up the matter. The MAWIGA petitioners, whose houses had been illegally sold, expressed dissatisfaction with the Department''s provisions for several reasons, such as the size of the properties allocated, and the level of redress arising from the fraudulent activity by municipal and provincial officials. The Committee set deadlines for the resolution of these matters. In a previous meeting, the petitioners had accepted the offers to land in the presence of the Committee. It was then agreed that the City of Tshwane (CoT), the national Department, and the Gauteng Department of Human Settlements, would build houses on the 50 m² allocated. Two petitioners later indicated they would accept this offer, while one other rejected it. The fourth petitioner had still not received a title deed to his property. The CoT had said that they would fast-track the title deed process, and had then advised that they were unable to finish this process as the land in question belonged to a private entity. For these reasons, the', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38593/', 0),
    (38671, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-03-20', 'Material Irregularities in the Human Settlements Portfolio; Consequence Management in Transgressions Cases by Provinces; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee was briefed in a virtual meeting by the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA) on progress regarding material irregularities within the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) portfolio. The DHS also reported back on consequence management action to deal with transgressions in the provinces. The AGSA took the Committee through the material irregularities and the associated financial losses. The accountability ecosystem was explained, along with recommendations for all the role players in the human settlements portfolio. The DHS took the Committee through a detailed table reflecting the material irregularities in the provinces, whether action had been taken or not taken, and if consequence management had been implemented. Concerns were raised about the termination of construction contracts, and the reasons for the terminations. Members asked if the DHS had any policies in place to deal with contractors that were guilty of non-performance or breach of contract, and what its plans were to ensure that underperformance was avoided in the future. The agreements with contractors should be clear. It was suggested that contractors who underperformed or did not perform at all should be barred from government projects. Concerns were raised about the impact of the "construction mafia," and the effect that AGSA''s new powers to make referrals to other investigating bodies would have. There had to be processes in place for employee misconduct, especially where over-payments were made to service providers. The right medication must be applied to this cancer of corruption. The Deputy Minister assured the Committee that the DHS would continue to intensify its monitoring role. While it could not regain the time lost, it would ensure that the impact of poor performance on the fiscus was minimal.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38671/', 0),
    (38726, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-03-27', 'Committee Legacy Report; NCOP Amendments on Housing Consumer Protection Bill', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met in a virtual meeting to discuss its legacy report, which served as a handover report for the new, incoming Parliament. The report consisted of a summarised version of the Committee''s work during the Sixth Parliament, from 2019 to 2024. While Members appreciated the report, they pointed out that several important aspects had been omitted. They said the report should be structured so that incoming Members who looked at it would be able to understand it. A decision was reached to redraft the report, and that it would be adopted next week. The Committee also considered and adopted the amendments by the Select Committee on Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs, Water and Sanitation and Human Settlements, on the Housing Consumer Protection Bill [B10D-2021], and the minutes of its three meetings during March.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/38726/', 0),
    (39037, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-07-10', 'Election of Chairperson; DHS, NHBRC, HDA, SHRA, NHFC, PPRA & CSOS Annual Performance Plan 2024/25', 'Human Settlements Housing Development Agency National Home Builders Registration Council Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority Report of the meeting to follow.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39037/', 0),
    (39081, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-07-12', 'Department of Human Settlements Budget Vote Report', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements convened on a virtual platform to consider and adopt the Committee Report on Budget Vote 33. The Committee Researcher presented the report on Budget Vote 33. He detailed the Department''s mandate, highlighting the constitutional right to adequate housing and the National Development Plan''s (NDP) vision for spatial transformation by 2050. He discussed the Medium Term Strategic Framework (MTSF) and the priorities outlined in the State of the Nation Address, including a R100 billion infrastructure fund allocation. Mr Makhanye analysed the Department''s performance and budget, noting a 4.4% nominal increase in the allocation to R33.1 billion, but a real decline of 0.32% after inflation. He outlined observations and recommendations, including concerns about budget reductions, housing application backlogs, unspent provincial grants, and the need for timely legislation on human settlements. Members provided inputs and sought clarifications on various points. Clarifications were sought about the National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC) and its inspection mandates, the absence of details on the Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS) digital platform, and the strategy for unblocking stalled projects. There were also questions on whether the Annual Performance Plan (APP) was included in specific observations and if inflation was considered in the draft budget to avoid a real decline. The report was adopted.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39081/', 0),
    (39301, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-08-21', 'Induction Workshop: engagement with DHS and entities; Committee support staff role; Committee Legacy Report', 'Human Settlements The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements had an induction workshop with the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) on its mandate, core business, programmes, projects, policies, and lessons learned in the past five years, including its entities. The Committee also discussed the roles of the supporting staff, and the legacy report covering the parliamentary term from 2019 to 2024. The DHS said it had a concurrent mandate and function involving all three branches of government. Its main service included planning, policy, regulatory, monitoring and evaluation, research and the provision of support to the sector partners. The provincial departments and municipalities were responsible for ensuring the implementation of human settlements at the local level. The budget structure was allocated in terms of five programmes: administration, integrated human settlements planning and development, the informal settlements upgrading programme, the rental and social housing programme, and the affordable housing programme. The DHS had received a qualified audit outcome with findings for the last few years. The Committee was briefed on the conditional human settlement grants, the purpose of which was to provide funding for the progressive realisation of access to adequate housing through the creation of sustainable and integrated human settlements. There was an informal settlements upgrading partnership grant for provinces and metropolitan municipalities, which was to provide funding to facilitate a programmatic and inclusive approach to upgrading informal settlements. The urban settlements development grant had been established with the purpose of supplementing the capital revenues of metropolitan municipalities in order to implement infrastructure projects that promote equitable, integrated, productive, inclusive and sustainable urban development. The Committee indicated that it was more interested in what the DHS was doing on a daily basis. Concerns were raise', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39301/', 0),
    (39314, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-08-22', 'Induction Workshop: engagement with DHS and entities (day 2)', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlement met to hear presentations by seven Department of Human Settlements entities on their work. This was the second day of the Committee’s induction, getting to understand its portfolio in the new Seventh Parliament. The briefings referred to efforts to provide affordable housing, the upgrading of informal settlements, issues of spatial planning and social justice, the registration of home builders and the development of black property practitioners. Members raised concerns about inadequate spending on housing by provinces and local governments. They emphasised the need for greater communication with communities and local councils in the planning of housing projects.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39314/', 0),
    (39359, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-08-28', 'AGSA Induction Session; DHS MTSF Performance; with Minister', 'The Committee met to be briefed by the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA) as part of the process of inducting the Committee on the organisation’s mandate. The AGSA''s presentation provided a historical context of the sixth administration''s audits, emphasising the importance of oversight, accountability, and governance. The AG highlighted a significant gap between audit outcomes and the actual experiences of citizens, noting that clean audits do not necessarily correlate with positive service delivery. This prompted a strategic shift towards ensuring that audit outcomes lead to tangible improvements in citizens'' lives, particularly in sectors like housing. The AG''s office stressed the need for public entities to not only comply with financial reporting but also to demonstrate effective service delivery. The presentation also outlined the accountability ecosystem within the South African public sector, emphasising that improving accountability and service delivery is a collective responsibility involving various stakeholders. Effective leadership was identified as crucial for fostering a culture of integrity and compliance. The AG noted that many public entities were currently categorised as "yellow," indicating unqualified audits with findings, which reflects a need for improvement in internal controls and performance reporting. The Department of Human Settlements (DHS) subsequently briefed the Committee on its performance under the Medium-Term Strategic Framework (MTSF) for 2019-2024, highlighting achievements and lessons learned. The discussion highlighted the need for the Committee to actively investigate unmet targets, enhance internal systems, and strengthen oversight mechanisms. Additionally, issues related to the national housing needs register and its correlation with the housing subsidy system were raised, indicating significant gaps in addressing the needs of vulnerable citizens.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39359/', 0),
    (39412, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-09-04', 'DHS strategy to unblock projects & support to provincial departments & municipalities that are failing to spend their budgets', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met with the national Department of Human Settlements to discuss the strategy to unblock projects across the country. The Department stated that for the current financial year, there were 100 blocked projects focused on unblocking. It had devised a draft strategy to address the stalled projects, and the Portfolio Committee was required to provide feedback. The Members of the Committee raised several questions concerning the stalled projects, the reasons for projects being delayed or abandoned, such as the activities of the construction mafia, the lack of money to fully address the stalled projects, the process of appointing contractors, and what consequences were implemented when contractors did not complete their projects. Members provided feedback on the draft strategy, highlighting the need for close cooperation with other departments, provinces, and municipalities as well as engagement with communities. For instance, had the Department of Human Settlements engaged with other departments, such as the police, to develop a strategy to combat illegal occupations and invasions of housing developments?', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39412/', 0),
    (39464, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-09-11', 'DHS Q4 2023/24 & Q1 2024/25 Performance; with Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to consider the performance of the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) for the fourth quarter of 2023/2024 and the first quarter of 2024/2025. The Chairperson acknowledged the Department''s ongoing efforts to address the backlog of title deeds and highlighted concerns about unspent allocated funds in some provinces. The Minister commended the leadership within the Department and identified poor performance in specific areas during the first quarter as partly due to a lack of political leadership and highlighted particular provinces where expenditure was an issue. The performance report for the fourth quarter revealed a strong overall expenditure of approximately R31.2 billion, representing 98% of the budget. While there was notable success in several housing programmes, challenges remained, particularly related to delays in procurement and project execution. The Department also acknowledged that some municipalities faced budget cuts, impacting their ability to fully utilise funds. In examining the first quarter performance, mixed outcomes were noted among metropolitan municipalities. Some showed impressive expenditure rates, while others underperformed significantly, particularly in the Informal Settlements Upgrading Partnership Grant. Emergency housing expenditure was also low, with only 13% utilised, highlighting the need for improved planning and execution. A robust discussion ensued, with Committee Members questioning the effectiveness of the Emergency Housing Fund and the Department''s disaster management processes. Concerns were raised regarding the Department''s response to natural disasters and its use of emergency funding. Members expressed the necessity for stricter measures to ensure financial resources are effectively allocated and used. In response, officials from the Department provided insights into ongoing efforts to improve project execution and address procurement challenges. They acknowledged t', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39464/', 0),
    (39516, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-09-18', 'SITA challenges in assisting DHS to digitise the Beneficiary List', 'The Portfolio Committee met to consider the concerns of the Department of Human Settlements (DHS), which had indicated it was not confident that the State Information Technology Agency (SITA) was the appropriate service provider for the development, release, training, support and maintenance of the planned National Digital Human Settlements Management System (NDHSMS). The Department updated the Committee on the challenges of the newly proposed system, which aimed to assist the DHS in digitising its beneficiary list. The Minister had asked it to develop a more reliable and interactive system to replace the current housing subsidy system (HSS). The new system would allow citizens to apply for housing products online, and select the most appropriate housing products based on their current situation. The DHS would be able to evaluate the application based on information provided and inform the citizens about the outcome of their application, or propose alternative housing products if their first application was not successful, or provide reasons for their application not being deemed successful based on the various rules associated with the different housing products. The Department, through SITA, was responsible for hosting, maintaining, supporting, and facilitating training arrangements on the HSS. The HSS environment also provided for operational and specific reporting requirements to enable provinces and municipalities to report, based on applicable legislative and internal requirements. The current HSS had, however, proved to be unreliable and vulnerable to beneficiary list manipulation in certain instances. The DHS said it had identified various issues related to the proposal received from SITA, such as why the departmental inputs had not been reflected in the presentation. There was no clarity on the technical details of the proposal, why data import and export interfaces had been excluded, if the other modules of the proposed solution for business plans and gran', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39516/', 0),
    (39657, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-10-16', 'Human Settlements Portfolio Audit Outcomes; DHS, NHBRC & NHFC 2023/24 Annual Reports; with Minister', 'Human Settlements National Housing Finance Corporation National Home Builders Registration Council The Portfolio Committee convened to evaluate the financial and non-financial performance of the Department of Human Settlements and its entities for the 2023/24 financial year. The meeting included presentations from the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA), the National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC), and the National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC). The AGSA''s report highlighted that no department had achieved a clean audit, with only 70% of planned housing units delivered and just 40% of medium-term strategic framework targets met. The report pointed out significant amounts of irregular expenditure and ongoing challenges in project management, and emphasised that many issues stemmed from inadequate internal controls. The AG noted that while some improvements were evident, substantial work remained to enhance compliance and accountability within the Department and its entities. The NHBRC addressed several critical issues, including delays in resolving disputes related to key performance indicators. It reported a historical balance of R710 million in irregular expenditure due to non-compliance with procurement procedures, with R524 million still being addressed. Consequence management was being improved through training initiatives following a maturity assessment that had identified gaps in policies not aligned with National Treasury regulations. In light of a recent building collapse in George, an internal investigation had been initiated due to violations by the builder, who had failed to enrol the structure with the NHBRC before construction began. During discussions, Committee Members raised concerns about the NHBRC''s accountability and performance. The Chairperson expressed dissatisfaction with some responses given during the meeting, indicating that they were dismissive and lacked depth. Members questioned how the NHBRC could enhance its process', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39657/', 0),
    (39671, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-10-18', 'SHRA, HDA, PPRA & CSOS 2023/24 Annual Reports', 'Video Community Schemes Ombud Service Housing Development Agency Social Housing Regulatory Authority Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority The Portfolio Committee convened to discuss the annual reports of four entities of the Department of Human Settlements -- the Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA), the Housing Development Agency (HDA), the Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA), and the Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS). The HDA highlighted the impact of its 2022 turnaround strategy, which had raised its performance from 29% in 2022 with a qualified audit, to 91% with an unqualified audit this year. A five-year irregular expenditure had been reduced by 90%, thanks to an electronic records system that ensured data integrity in audits. Although R36 million in irregular expenditure had arisen from an unresolved payment process, no new irregular expenses had been reported due to stricter controls. The CSOS reported its adjudication of 4 326 cases, with reference made to specific cases awaiting adjudication. Of its 23 targets, 19 had been achieved. In 2022/23, the entity had had a qualified audit outcome, but in 2022/23, there was an unqualified audit opinion with limited material findings -- and very close to a clean audit. In the current year, the entity has received a qualified audit opinion. Concerns have been raised regarding delays in processing cases, highlighting the need to improve the efficiency of the adjudication process to ensure the timely resolution of disputes. The Committee called for measures to streamline operations and reduce the backlog. The SHRA highlighted the organisation''s efforts to promote sustainable social housing development, emphasising its role in facilitating access to affordable housing. The entity received a clean audit during this financial year, and out of the 25 performance indicators, nine were related to transformation, and six of these were achieved. The report revealed significant achievements, inc', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39671/', 0),
    (39712, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-10-23', 'Human Settlements Budgetary Review and Recommendation Report', 'Video Budgetary Review and Recommendations Report (BRRR) The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met in a virtual meeting to consider its Budget Review and Recommendations Report (BRRR) for the human settlements portfolio. Members complained that they had received a copy of the report very late, which had prevented them from analysing it thoroughly, and asserted that this might have been a deliberate ploy, considering the poor quality of the contents. They cited numerous examples where recommendations made by the Committee had been omitted, as well as several grammatical errors. They agreed that the Committee could not accept the report in its current form. The Committee staff was directed to listen to the recordings of previous meetings, as well as the current meeting, reflect on what had been raised, and redo the entire report for adoption at a later date.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39712/', 0),
    (39775, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-10-30', 'Ga-Rankuwa/Mabopane Petition; Breede Valley Petition', 'Video In a virtual meeting, the Committee received updates from the provincial Departments of Human Settlements of North West and Gauteng, the City of Tshwane (CoT) and the North West Housing Corporation (NWHC), on the Ga-Rankuwa/Mabopane petition. It was also updated by the Department of Human Settlements in the Western Cape and the Breede Valley Municipality on the Breede Valley petition, with a progress report from the national Department of Human Settlements (DHS). These were not new matters before the Committee. The commitments under discussion had been facilitated by the 6th Parliament’s Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements. The Committee in the 7th Parliament was concerned about the lack of collaboration between the various spheres of government to resolve this old matter. The petition concerned the alleged maladministration of the North West Housing Corporation and the City of Tshwane authorities, which had unlawfully sold and transferred the petitioners'' houses. The corrective measures had yet to be carried out, in spite of two investigations, one carried out by the Public Protector in 2018, and the other by the City of Tshwane in 2014. To guarantee that this issue was settled quickly, the Committee urged increased cooperation between the several branches of government. To bring the case to a definitive conclusion, the parties pledged to follow the revised timetables. The Committee resolved that this matter should be treated as a project, with clear project management and coordination. It also directed that the matters be resolved within six months. The Committee also expressed concern that, despite numerous meetings, the New Mandela Square 652 project in the Breede Valley Municipality in the Western Cape had not been resolved. The Committee was updated on a petition that the 6th Parliament Committee had received regarding the absence of services in the ward, and top structures that had not yet been built. The Committee directed that regular progress re', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39775/', 0),
    (39804, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-11-01', 'Human Settlements Budgetary Review and Recommendation Report', 'Video Budgetary Review & Recommendations Reports BRRR The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements convened to further deliberate on the Committee''s Budgetary Review and Recommendations Report (BRRR). During the meeting, Members enhanced the recommendations of the report on the Department’s financial management, housing quality control measures, and strategic planning processes for emergency housing allocation, highlighting areas requiring immediate improvement. Following extensive discussions, the Committee agreed on several amendments aimed at reinforcing accountability mechanisms within the Department. These included calls for regular financial audits, enhanced financial oversight, and targeted training for staff in financial management. Members stressed the importance of provincial accountability in project execution, advocating stronger oversight at this level to prevent inefficiencies and improved housing delivery timelines. The discussion also drew attention to the Emergency Housing Fund. Members underscored the Minister''s recent endorsement of the fund’s devolution, a strategy aimed at empowering local communities with tailored housing solutions. The Committee highlighted that such a shift could expedite responses to urgent housing needs, allowing for quicker deployment of temporary residential units and refined profiling of community requirements. However, concerns were raised over certain omissions in the report, including lifestyle audits for housing inspectors and recent commitments from the Minister regarding the Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA). A motion to adopt the report with amendments was subsequently tabled. However, this motion was met with opposition from representatives of the MK and EFF parties, who formally registered their rejection of the BRRR.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39804/', 0),
    (39849, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-11-13', 'Title Deeds; Repurposing Old Buildings; Social Housing Growth Plan', 'The Portfolio Committee expressed frustration over the recurring absence of the Minister and Deputy Minister from its meetings, emphasising the need for accountability and better communication. A progress report was provided on title deeds issuance and registration by the Department of Human Settlements (DHS). The priority project aims to eliminate the backlog of over two million unissued title deeds. The continuing challenges issuing title deeds are due to incomplete township establishments, lack of bulk services, and resource constraints. The “Title Deed Friday” campaign is a community education campaign to expedite title deed distribution and promote inheritance planning. It calls on beneficiaries of government-subsidized homes to collect their title deeds at municipality offices. Committee members raised concerns about inadequate provincial performance and delays, insufficient staffing, resource allocation, and suggested direct national interventions and reallocations to address inefficiencies. The Housing Development Agency (HDA) presented its Inner City Regeneration Programme focusing on repurposing old buildings and addressing illegal occupation. Challenges include municipal inefficiencies, budget constraints, and predatory practices in informal housing. The Social Housing Growth Plan was presented by the Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA). Its goal is to increase affordable rental units significantly. Challenges include construction delays, criminality, and poor property management. SHRA requested Committee support to ensure it is well funded to address the plethora of challenges. Challenges identified: • Limited funding and inter-departmental collaboration on infrastructure projects. • Delays caused by municipal inefficiencies and political hurdles such as in Free State. • Criminal activities illegal building occupations and construction mafias, hinder progress. Way Forward: • Enhanced intergovernmental collaboration to address infrastructure and fu', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39849/', 0),
    (39912, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-11-20', 'Illegal Occupation of Houses and Land & Illegal Sales of State Subsidised Houses; Upgrade of Informal Settlements in the Stellenbosch area; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Department of Human Settlements (DHS) met with the Portfolio Committee to present its strategies to combat illegal land occupations and the unauthorised resale of subsidised housing. They emphasised the Department''s focus on protecting public assets, ensuring equitable housing access, and maintaining subsidy integrity through preventative and reactive measures. Key challenges included housing shortages driving illegal land occupations, unauthorised occupation of subsidised homes, and informal sales bypassing legal processes. To address these issues, the DHS aimed to strengthen legislation, such as the Prevention of Illegal Evictions (PIE) Act and the Housing Amendment Act, streamline eviction processes, and enhance monitoring and enforcement capacity. Proposed interventions included building public trust through transparency, raising awareness about legal housing options, and forming partnerships for inner-city housing projects. The Department underscored the need for legislative reform, public education, and collaboration with municipalities and provinces, to address these challenges comprehensively. The Western Cape Department of Infrastructure presented on informal settlements and housing projects in Stellenbosch, highlighting key areas such as Kayamandi, Langrug and Klapmuts. Strategies to prevent unlawful occupation included land audits, settlement categorisation, and integrating informal areas into municipal spatial plans. Upgrading projects funded under the Upgrading of Informal Settlements Program (UISP) aimed to enhance basic services, including sanitation and electricity. Key initiatives include the Zone O and Enkanini projects in Kayamandi, the Jamestown Housing Project, and the Langrug Dam project, addressing safety risks. Progress was noted on serviced sites, Wendy house replacements, and property transfers for development in areas like Pniel. The presentation emphasised proactive planning, collaboration across government levels, and addressin', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39912/', 0),
    (39927, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-11-21', 'Ga-Rankuwa/Mabopane Petition', 'The Committee met with the petitioners in the City of Tshwane and the National Department of Human Settlements (NDHS) responded about progress in the Mabopane/Ga-Rankuwa petition cases which included title deed acquisition, fraudulent resale of property and forced removals. Committee members insisted on immediate NDHS action; asked about punitive action taken against corrupt government officials and said that bank mortgage processes must be investigated. It was suggested that there be a discussion on the operation of the housing corporation entities.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39927/', 0),
    (39937, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-11-22', 'White Paper on Human Settlements; Provincial Departments of Human Settlements on strategies and plans to unblock blocked projects; removal of asbestos roofs; eradication of mud houses and beneficiary lists', 'The meeting took place in Gauteng. We are trying to obtain information and will update the record as soon as we receive it.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39937/', 0),
    (39982, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2024-11-27', 'PPRA on the progress made in the Transformation Agenda and Transformation Fund; DHS Q2 2024/25 Performance', 'Video Report of the meeting to follow.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39982/', 0),
    (40142, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-01-30', 'Committee Training & Business, Initial Briefing on SAHRC Report and Legal Opinion on Court Judgement', 'Committee content advisor initial briefing on SAHRC report (awaited document) The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements held an in-person meeting to deal with a range of matters. Members were first guided on how to complete claim forms for travel reimbursements, which required receipts for each journey. The discussion covered various claimable expenses, including parking fees, toll gates, and travel costs incurred through ride-hailing services like Uber and Bolt. It was clarified that while some travel expenses, such as flights, were covered by entitlements, others, like toll fees, were not. Members were advised on the correct forms and documentation needed for different types of claims. Concerns were raised regarding Members travelling from smaller towns with limited flight options. Some Members requested access to larger airports, such as OR Tambo, for logistical convenience. It was confirmed that they could be assisted by registering alternative airport options in such situations. A key point of discussion was whether Members using their entitlements for Committee-related travel could be reimbursed by the Committee. They were encouraged to obtain budget approval from Committee management before undertaking oversight trips to avoid personal entitlement depletion. Concerns were raised about the possibility of double claims, with Members being reminded that all claims were subject to submission to the South African Revenue Service (SARS). A structured claim verification process was in place, requiring proof of attendance at meetings. This included attendance registers and departure confirmations, particularly for multi-day trips. The discussion touched on claim rates for international travel, which were calculated based on SARS guidelines. It was noted that Members of Parliament (MPs) receive a lower daily allowance compared to provincial government officials, raising concerns about fairness in budget allocations. However, adjustments to these rates would need to', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40142/', 0),
    (40149, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-01-31', 'CC judgment on the City of Cape Town’s implementation of the national housing programme; SAHRC report on housing matters in North West; with Minister and Deputy Minister present', 'Charnell Commando and Others v City of Cape Town and Another (CCT 49/23) [2024] ZACC 27 (20 December 2024) SAHRC report on housing matters in North West The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to discuss the South African Human Rights Commission’s (SAHRC''s) report on poor workmanship and non-payment of contractors by the North West Provincial Department of Human Settlements, and to be briefed on the Constitutional Court judgment concerning the City of Cape Town’s implementation of the national housing programme for emergency accommodation. The Chairperson welcomed the Minister and Deputy Minister, and outlined key outstanding matters requiring attention, including the George building collapse, the National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC) investigation, the Social Housing Regulatory Authority matter, and issues related to the National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC) and housing petitions. The North West Department of Human Settlements presented its response to the SAHRC report, detailing steps taken to address incomplete housing projects, budget cuts, contract terminations, and financial irregularities. They had begun terminating contracts with non-performing contractors, and provided a list of projects that had been affected since 2023. They addressed financial management issues, including the impact of budget cuts, late payments to contractors, and ongoing challenges with beneficiary list revisions by municipalities. The presentation highlighted efforts to improve communication and transparency in project management, while acknowledging systemic inefficiencies that required further intervention. Committee Members raised pointed questions about accountability, financial mismanagement and contractor oversight. They questioned the enforcement of SAHRC recommendations, and called for an independent monitoring framework. Concern was expressed over the lack of consequence management for terminated contractors, warning of a cycle of incomplete proje', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40149/', 0),
    (40249, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-02-19', 'Upgrading of Slovo Park Informal Settlements Petition', 'Video Gauteng Department of Human Settlements presentations (awaited document) The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements convened to discuss the upgrading of Slovo Park informal settlement, focusing on the long-standing delays in implementation, the 2016 High Court order, and the broader challenges affecting service delivery. The petitioners highlighted their frustration over the decades-long delays in upgrading Slovo Park. Despite a 2016 High Court ruling mandating an in-situ upgrade, progress remained minimal. Residents continued to face severe service delivery failures, including the lack of sanitation, water, and road infrastructure. The petitioners called for transparency in budget allocations, requesting a full audit of previous township proclamations which had failed to materialise. Concerns were also raised over the tragic death of a 16-year-old resident, allegedly linked to inadequate service delivery. The petitioners stressed the need for political will and an urgent intervention to ensure that commitments were translated into tangible improvements. The City of Johannesburg (CoJ) and the Gauteng Department of Human Settlements (DHS) provided updates on their interventions. The CoJ assured the Committee that processes had been resuscitated and that the City would hold monthly oversight meetings to track progress. New consultants were being appointed and planning approvals were underway, while interim services were being assessed in collaboration with Johannesburg Water. The DHS said that despite budget constraints, Slovo Park would remain a priority over the next three years, and that funding allocations would be reviewed to ensure continued progress. Committee Members raised serious concerns regarding the ongoing delays and the lack of consequence management for underperformance. They questioned why no significant progress had been made nearly nine years after the 2016 court order. They criticised the excessive reliance on consultants, and requested a d', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40249/', 0),
    (40281, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-02-26', 'Briefing by the Department of Human Settlements on 2024/25 Third Quarter Performance', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements convened virtually to discuss the 2024/25 third quarter performance of the Department of Human Settlements. The Department provided in-depth presentations on the Department''s performance, emphasising key achievements, challenges, plans and finances. It reported achieving all 28 set targets, with improved internal verification processes, but noted significant underspending in goods and services (42%), informal settlements (65%), and capital assets (24%). The Department highlighted procurement delays, grant framework finalisation issues, and slow fund disbursement. Committee Members raised concerns over contractor non-payment, financial inefficiencies, and the backlog in title deeds and informal settlement upgrades. One Member criticised excessive travel expenses, prompting the Chairperson to request further scrutiny. Members asked questions about the spread of informal settlements, the housing backlog, the rationale for grant reallocations, fraud and corruption in the Department, title deeds registration, low-quality construction, and emergency housing. They drew attention to the misalignment between the Department’s 100% achievement of its performance indicators and significant underspending. The Chairperson requested reports on title deed distribution and non-metro accredited municipalities, and suggested a Committee oversight visit to a Community Residential Unit project in the North West Province.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40281/', 0),
    (40310, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-03-05', 'GaRankuwa/Mabopane and Breede Valley Petitions', 'Video The Portfolio Committee met to follow up on the GaRankuwa/Mabopane petitions and review the situation in the Breede Valley. The meeting focused on key issues related to the petitioners, township formalisation, land transfers, housing projects, and accountability for past investigations. The Committee expressed deep concern about the lack of enforcement of previous investigation findings, particularly the 2014 and 2018 Public Protector reports. It questioned why responsible individuals had not been held accountable for the issues raised in these reports, and discussed the potential of mediation as a means to resolve them. Financial matters were a significant point of discussion, with Members stressing that all financial commitments should be properly documented to comply with legal requirements. The increasing cost of housing units was acknowledged as a challenge, but the Committee commended the Department for securing additional funding from the private sector. Members questioned whether any disciplinary action had been taken as a result of the Special Investigating Unit’s findings. The Committee debated the efforts that had been made to engage with petitioners, especially regarding unresolved cases, and expressed concerns about the adequacy of the budget for the New Mandela Square project. There was uncertainty about whether infrastructure development had been fully accounted for, and questions were raised regarding the readiness of infrastructure, fire-prone housing structures, and the impact of relocating residents. Members raised concerns about the negotiation process for land acquisition, particularly regarding potential profiteering by private landowners. It was suggested that the City consider using the Expropriation Act to address land shortages. The Committee emphasised the need for greater accountability, clearer budget planning, mediation for land disputes, and better engagement with affected communities to ensure sustainable and legally compliant h', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40310/', 0),
    (40357, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-03-12', 'Metropolitan municipalities: USDG and ISUPG performance, Management of Housing Beneficiary List, Informal settlements upgrading programme, plans to curb land invasions; with Deputy Minister', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements was briefed by the metropolitan municipalities of Buffalo City, Nelson Mandela Bay, Mangaung and eThekwini on the performance of the Urban Development Grant (USDG) and Informal Settlements Upgrading Partnership Grant (ISUPG). The Committee was also briefed on illegal land invasions and the management of housing beneficiary lists by the metros. The national Department of Human Settlements informed the Committee that it acknowledged the intention of National Treasury to withhold budgets from municipalities that were not performing financially. A meeting of the national and provincial housing ministers had supported a process to review the grants. The Department would do a thorough review of the capacities of the metros and how they could repurpose themselves to ensure that bulk infrastructure was being delivered. Monitoring would be strengthened to ensure the grants were well spent. The Buffalo City Metropolitan Municipality reported that it had spent 45 percent, or R241.4 million, of its USDG budget by 31 January 2024. Further spending commitments would take the proportion to 76 percent. The Metro confirmed that it was implementing projects in line with cash flow projections and that the total allocated budget would be fully spent by the end of the current financial year. Buffalo City reported that it had spent 27 percent of its ISUPG budget of R304.7 million as of 31 January 2025. The total allocated budget would be fully spent by the end of the current financial year. The Nelson Mandela Bay Metropolitan Municipality reported that at the end of March 2025, the spending of the USDG was at 32 percent and ISUPG expenditure was at 49 percent. Funds were being diverted from non-performing projects to other programmes, particularly sanitation. The budget for the grants would be spent towards the end of the financial year. The appointment of a chief financial officer would bring stability to the finance department. Strategies we', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40357/', 0),
    (40422, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-03-19', 'Innovative Building Technology (IBT): Moladi, CSIR, Agrément South Africa', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements discussed innovative approaches to addressing South Africa''s housing challenges. The meeting featured presentations from the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research (CSIR), Agrément South Africa (ASA) and Moladi. The CSIR outlined its role in fostering socioeconomic prosperity through innovation, highlighting contributions such as the People''s Housing Process, Housing Subsidy System, and research on alternative building technologies. Current tools like the Green Book for climate change adaptation and Urban Growth Modelling for infrastructure planning were discussed. The CSIR emphasized its alignment with the Human Settlements White Paper and its role as a key technology partner in policy implementation. Agrément SA’s mandate to certify non-standardized construction products, ensuring safety and innovation, was explained. The presentation detailed ASA''s performance criteria and technical assessment processes, as well as its quality assurance measures. ASA highlighted its global connections and commitment to improving safety in the construction industry. Moladi presented its innovative building technology, which uses reusable plastic formwork to create affordable, durable housing. The system empowers communities by training unskilled workers to build their own homes, addressing South Africa''s housing backlog and unemployment crisis. The environmental benefits of Moladi''s approach were emphasized, and a call was made for government adoption of performance-based norms for innovative building technologies. Committee members raised questions about the implementation of CSIR research, the role of ASA in preventing construction failures, and Moladi''s compliance with BBBEE policies. Questions were raised about the structural integrity of Moladi''s buildings, the need for skills development in the construction industry, and the challenges of informal settlement upgrading. In response, CSIR emphasized the need for more engagem', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40422/', 0),
    (40512, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-04-02', 'Metros: USDG reports, Beneficiary lists, Informal settlement upgrades, Land invasions; with Ministry', 'The Committee met with the Department of Human Settlements and four metros -- the cities of Cape Town, Tshwane, Ekurhuleni and Johannesburg -- to address budget expenditure issues, the management of beneficiaries, the upgrading of informal settlements, and land invasions. The Minister highlighted how all metros were struggling in one form or another, and raised concern over the lack of cooperation from Executive Mayors and Members of Mayoral Committees (MMCs), despite numerous attempts by the Department to engage with them in attempts to find solutions to their challenges. She emphasised the need for joint cooperation from all parties. The Department''s delegates referred to National Treasury''s directive to stop providing a portion of the Urban Settlements Development Grant (USDG) and the Informal Settlements Upgrading Partnership Grant (ISUPG) to metros that were not performing as of 31 December. They highlighted the lack of project completion from the metros, and called for equitable, integrated, productive, inclusive and sustainable development within human settlements. The metros made presentations to provide a full picture to the Committee, highlighting the challenges they faced and the strategies in place to address them. Focus was placed on USDG and ISUPG strategies and addressing issues of land invasions, as well as allocating homes to beneficiaries in a transparent and equitable manner. Members raised concerns over recurring issues, such as the lack of capacity, water, sanitation and electricity challenges, the construction mafia and the distribution of title deeds.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40512/', 0),
    (40530, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-04-04', 'DHS investigations, suspensions, resignations, reinstatements, George building collapse; with Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee convened to receive a detailed briefing from the Minister of Human Settlements on a range of pressing issues concerning the Department and its associated entities. One of the most urgent matters presented was the George building collapse and the ensuing 250-page investigation report received by the Minister on 26 March. The report revealed significant systemic failures within the National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC). The Minister explained that the project in question had begun construction before the completion and proper approval of the enrolment documentation. Critical design plans and structural engineering submissions were either missing or delayed, and the NHBRC''s oversight mechanisms had failed at multiple levels. The NHBRC''s chief executive officer (CEO) had been suspended in November 2024 for not demonstrating appropriate urgency and for misleading the Council about the suspension status of implicated senior officials. Two executive managers had been under the CEO’s supervision, despite being on probation and delivering unsatisfactory performance. During discussion, Committee Members expressed concern over the lack of consequence management for both internal officials and the implicated construction company, Liatel Developments. Questions were raised about the role of the municipality, the handling of enrolment documents, and the structural integrity evaluation process. Some Members also queried whether any criminal proceedings or blacklisting actions had been initiated. The Minister clarified that the root cause of the collapse lay in the deviation from processes when the structure was transformed from a single-storey to a multi-storey development without appropriate regulatory oversight. There were also serious procedural failures, including incorrect use of system login credentials, lack of supervision, and tampering with the global positioning system (GPS) after the incident. The Minister confirmed that disci', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40530/', 0),
    (40588, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-04-23', 'DHS, NHBRC & CSOS 2025/26 Annual Performance Plans (incl AGSA input); with Minister', 'Human Settlements Strategic Plan Community Schemes Ombud Service Strategic Plan National Home Builders Registration Council Strategic Plan The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements convened to review the Annual Performance Plans (APPs) and strategic plans of the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) and its entities. The meeting highlighted several recurring concerns raised by Members of Parliament (MPs), focusing on governance, service delivery, financial accountability, and sector-specific challenges. Governance and Institutional Stability A significant portion of the discussion revolved around governance issues within the sector''s entities. MPs expressed concern over the absence of boards in key entities like the Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS) and the National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC). The Minister acknowledged delays in appointing boards, citing failed security vetting processes and skill shortages. The Chairperson criticised the practice of appointing accounting officers as interim authorities, warning that it could compromise audits. The National Housing Builders Registration Council (NHBRC''s) appointment of its Chief Financial Officer (CFO) as acting Chief Executive Officer (CEO) was particularly contentious, with MPs labelling it illegal and detrimental to oversight. The Minister defended the decision as a temporary measure but pledged to expedite board appointments. MPs scrutinised the Department''s ability to deliver housing and address backlogs. Issues such as title deed delays, substandard housing, and the eradication of asbestos were raised. Members condemned the living conditions in hostels and informal settlements, urging immediate action. The Minister attributed title deed delays to bureaucratic complexities and pledged to collaborate with provinces on asbestos eradication. MPs also questioned the lack of measurable indicators in APPs for critical issues like emergency housing, with the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA) notin', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40588/', 0),
    (40691, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-05-14', 'Lifestyle audit of NHBRC inspectors; DHS intervention in flood-affected provinces (with Deputy Minister)', 'Video The Committee convened a meeting to receive a briefing from the Department of Human Settlements on two key matters: the status of lifestyle audits conducted within the National Home Builders Registration Council, and the Department’s interventions in provinces recently affected by floods. The Committee was informed that the lifestyle audits had been initiated in response to concerns about maladministration and potential corruption within the National Home Builders Registration Council. The audits, which focused on senior management staff, were conducted through an independent service provider. The Committee questioned whether the decision to outsource the audits stemmed from a lack of internal capacity and sought clarity on when the service provider was appointed, how long the audit process had been underway, and the costs involved. In addition, Members of the Committee requested information on the number of entities that had completed lifestyle audits, given the historical challenges they have faced with internal governance. They also inquired whether labour unions were consulted before the implementation of the audits. The Committee sought clarity on whether lifestyle audits would be institutionalised as a standard governance practice. Members expressed concern over the high number of inspectors from the National Home Builders Registration Council who are currently under investigation and raised questions about the transparency and independence of the audit process, particularly in cases where assessments of lifestyle and declared income may be subjective. Furthermore, the Committee asked whether the Council had benchmarked its audit approach against that of other institutions, and what lessons had been drawn to strengthen audit effectiveness. Members pointed to operational vulnerabilities, particularly the absence of a Chief Executive Officer, as a contributing factor to delays in the audit process. They requested further details regarding the audit methodo', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40691/', 0),
    (40751, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-05-21', 'NHBRC criteria for approving houses built; CIDB criteria for grading contractors; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Committee received briefings from the Construction Industry Development Board (CIDB) and the National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC) on contractor registration, enrolment protocols, and regulatory enforcement mechanisms in the housing and construction sectors. NHBRC emphasised inspection protocols, the enrolment process, and technical compliance in home building. CIDB outlined the legislative framework for grading contractors, the performance monitoring role of its registers, and upcoming amendments to improve inclusivity and oversight. Committee members raised questions about compliance enforcement, skills development and upgrading building contractors. Of particular concern was the delay in NHBRC investigation report on the George building collapse.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40751/', 0),
    (40805, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-05-28', 'Briefings on Prevention of Illegal Eviction from and Unlawful Occupation of Land Bill', 'The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to consider a motion of desirability on a Private Member’s Bill proposing amendments to the Prevention of Illegal Eviction from and Unlawful Occupation of Land Act (PIE Act). The Committee also received a briefing from the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) in response to the proposed Bill. A former Member of the Committee during the Sixth Parliament, presented the motion and the Bill. She explained that the amendments were prompted by municipal appeals for legislative reform to help manage growing incidents of unlawful land occupation. She stated that she did not object to the Department leading the amendment process, as long as urgent legislative attention was given to the matter. Members raised concern that the Member had introduced the Bill while the Department was already undertaking its own review of the PIE Act. Members from the African National Congress (ANC), Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF), uMkhonto weSizwe Party (MKP), and National Coloured Congress (NCC) objected to the Bill’s framing and intent, stating that it failed to acknowledge the historical context of land dispossession and the structural causes of landlessness in South Africa. The proposed five-year sentence for inciting unlawful occupation was strongly criticised as overly punitive, with Members arguing that it would criminalise vulnerable people rather than addressing housing backlogs and failures in land redistribution. Democratic Alliance (DA) Members supported the Bill, noting the severe burden illegal land invasions placed on municipalities. They argued that municipalities were struggling to deliver services due to the diversion of resources towards addressing unlawful occupations and emergency housing. While the Department of Human Settlements expressed support for certain provisions within the Bill — such as increased penalties for incitement and clearer judicial guidance — it rejected the Bill in its entirety, citing concerns over oper', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40805/', 0),
    (40869, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-06-04', 'First Home Finance Programme progress; NHFC allegations; with Minister', 'Video The First Home Finance Programme, previously known as FLISP, is a rebranded initiative under NHFC, aims to assist low- to middle-income households who do not qualify for RDP housing but struggle to secure commercial mortgages. The programme offers a sliding-scale subsidy based on income, with eligibility ranging from R3 501 to R22 000 per month. The Department of Human Settlements (DHS) briefing highlighted significant improvements in its uptake, particularly in rural areas, due to expanded eligibility criteria and partnerships with traditional leaders. However, challenges such as system automation delays, reputational risks from external originators, and potential funding shortfalls were noted. The discussion revealed discrepancies in provincial application data, prompting a commitment from the Department to provide audited figures. Members emphasised the need for broader public awareness and equitable provincial participation, with particular concern for underserved regions like the North West province. The second agenda item focused on governance challenges at NHFC, including allegations against the CEO. These allegations ranged from irregular office leases and unauthorised ex gratia payments to workplace bullying and misuse of company funds. The Director-General clarified that many matters were historical or under review by the Auditor-General and National Treasury. The Minister stressed the importance of due process, noting that the incoming NHFC Board would be tasked with investigating and resolving these issues within strict timelines. She had rejected ex gratia payments due to unmet performance thresholds and underscored the need for structural interventions to address staff morale. The Minister also addressed concerns about procurement irregularities, such as the escalated budget for an ERP system, and affirmed the Department’s commitment to transparency and accountability. Committee members raised pointed questions about the NHFC’s governance, with s', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40869/', 0),
    (40945, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-06-11', 'Housing Consumer Protection Act Regulations, Human Settlements Draft Bill, Title Deeds; Municipality Accreditation; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Department of Human Settlements (DHS) provided progress reports on the Human Settlements Draft Bill and the regulations under the Housing Consumer Protection Act, as well as the Title Restoration Project and the accreditation of municipalities to administer housing programmes. Discussions focused on the challenges municipalities face in issuing title deeds, delays in project completion, and the need for uniform policies to improve efficiency. Members raised concerns on the pace of service delivery and interdepartmental coordination, urging DHS to expedite implementation and provide clearer milestones.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40945/', 0),
    (41008, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-06-18', 'DHS, NHBRC, NHFC, SHRA, PPRA, HDA & CSOS 2025/26 Annual Performance Plans; with Deputy Minister', '2025/26 Annual Performance Plans The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements received briefings from the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) and its entities on their 2025/26 Annual Performance Plans (APPs), 2025–2030 Strategic Plans, and Budget Vote 33 allocations. Presentations were delivered by the DHS, Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS), National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC), National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC), Housing Development Agency (HDA), Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA), and the Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA). The Chairperson emphasised the importance of integrated and sustainable human settlements and highlighted enduring challenges such as informal settlements, land shortages, infrastructure constraints, and title deed backlogs. The Committee called on the Department to strengthen service delivery, especially in the upgrading of informal settlements and disaster recovery in areas affected by recent floods. The Director-General confirmed a stable three-year budget allocation of R101 billion, while outlining realistic title deed delivery targets, constrained by structural and legislative hurdles. Interventions include the establishment of an Inter-Ministerial Committee and proposed regulatory waivers for unproclaimed areas. The NHFC confirmed no changes to its budget or strategic targets since April and raised concern over the underfunding of the First Home Finance Programme, where demand far exceeds current allocations. The NHFC reiterated its goal of evolving into a fully-fledged Human Settlements Development Bank, but noted that full capitalisation remains a constraint. CSOS and NHFC outlined active debt recovery strategies, digital transformation efforts, and regulatory developments to address gaps in levy compliance and scheme registration. The NHBRC reported that it was on track to comply with the amended regulatory framework, which introduces stricter penalties for unregistered builders. T', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41008/', 0),
    (41078, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-06-25', 'Human Settlements Budget Vote Report Consideration; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements convened to adopt its report on Budget Vote 33. The report was presented by the content advisor, and thereafter the Members provided amendments as well as their inputs. A Member criticised the way the report read, and suggested that there needed to be a number of wording changes. Other Members were concerned that some critical information was not captured in the report, and requested that the content advisor add this information. There was also concern that the report made no mention of traditional leaders. The Chairperson advised the content advisor to contact Members to better understand their input in order to edit the report so that it could be adopted. The Deputy Minister addressed a few comments raised by Members, and also provided her thoughts on the report. The Committee agreed to meet again the following evening to adopt the report, following its amendment.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41078/', 0),
    (41102, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-06-26', 'Human Settlements Budget Vote Report', 'Video The Committee considered and adopted its report on the Department of Human Settlements Budget Vote. The Committee will debate the budget next week.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41102/', 0),
    (41268, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-07-11', 'Update on Petitions: MAWIGA, PHP Project, Slovo Park, Kgasoe, Mere Land, Masincedane & New Mandela Square', 'Video North West DHS presentation on Kgasoe housing project, Mere Land presentation and Western Cape presentation Update on Masincedane PHP project (awaited documents) The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements convened virtually to follow up on petitions and progress reports regarding human settlements interventions across various areas. It received updates on the petitions from Ga-Rankuwa/Mabopane (MAWIGA Petitioners), the Breede Valley Municipality, Strand Petitioners, Slovo Park Informal Settlements upgrading, Mr Kgasoe’s house, the Masincedane PHP Project, and the Breede Valley Municipality''s New Mandela Square. The Department of Human Settlements, supported by the City of Tshwane and the North West Provincial Department, briefed the Committee on progress relating to the MAWIGA petitioners (Ms Sepeng and Ms Ledingoane). It reported that appropriate land parcels had been identified and accepted by the petitioners. These sites had been linked to existing housing projects to accelerate procurement and construction processes. The anticipated timeline for the construction of top structures was during the 2026/27 financial year, subject to the conclusion of procurement processes and municipal approvals. The Committee expressed disappointment with the slow progress, noting that timeframes initially committed to during previous engagements had not been met. Concerns were raised over the inactive subsidy approval process, municipal delays, and the lack of accountability for protracted delays. The City of Tshwane was specifically asked to provide an update on the subsidy application for Ms Sepeng by the following Friday. The Department committed to intensifying intergovernmental coordination to ensure delivery. The North West Province provided a briefing on the Mere Land matter, a separate but related issue, following Tshwane''s presentation. The Committee also received updates on progress regarding the response to the other petitions, and reiterated the need for strong', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41268/', 0),
    (41301, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-07-16', 'Challenges in managing housing beneficiary list for military veterans; DHS Q4 2024/25 Performance; with Minister and Deputy Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met virtually to receive briefings from the Department of Military Veterans (DMV) and the Department of Human Settlements (DHS). The focus was on the challenges in managing the beneficiary list for military veterans'' housing support and the DHS''s fourth quarter performance as per its 2024/25 Annual Performance Plan (APP). The DMV outlined significant structural and operational challenges, including inaccurate and incomplete beneficiary databases, delays in verification, duplicate applications, insufficient land availability, illegal occupations, and an ineffective one-size-fits-all housing model. Only 20% of housing applications meet qualifying criteria, and many houses were found to have defects or lacked basic services. The DMV proposed reviewing housing regulations, income thresholds, and improving coordination with the DHS through a joint strategic session. Members expressed concern over inconsistent housing standards across provinces—specifically, the Free State’s deviation from national norms—delays in verifying beneficiaries (some unregistered even after 30 years), and housing defects in occupied units. The DHS explained that provincial increases in house sizes were politically driven but unsustainable and reiterated its mandate for construction while relying on the DMV for beneficiary lists and top-up subsidies. The DHS confirmed active housing construction nationwide, aiming to clear backlogs within three years. They also detailed challenges in enforcing contractor accountability after certification and outlined rectification programmes for defects. Committee Members recommended fast-tracking procurement for emergency housing, filling critical vacancies swiftly, and strengthening accountability for delays. Frustration was voiced over the slow progress and repeated issues, emphasising the need for a uniform housing model that respects veterans'' dignity. Questions were raised about ongoing funding despite the', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41301/', 0),
    (41491, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-09-03', 'Committee Strategic Plan; Garden Route District Municipality Oversight Visit', 'The central focus of the meeting was the draft Strategic Plan for 2024 - 2029. Members engaged in robust discussions on aligning the plan with the Committee’s mandate, including the Sustainable Development Goals, joint oversight opportunities with other parliamentary committees, and the need to improve accountability, public participation, and consequence management within municipalities. Concerns were raised about housing policy inconsistencies, weak follow-up on oversight visits, absence of clear objectives in the strategic plan; stronger SWOT analysis; international study tours, and addressing climate change through innovative building technologies. Members agreed on the need to enhance community engagement and participation strategies and to ensure proper reporting mechanisms, such as quarterly feedback reports, to monitor implementation. It was agreed that the draft Strategic Plan would be refined to reflect these discussions The Committee Report on Garden Route District Municipality Oversight Visit was considered and adopted. The importance of timely departmental report-backs on Committee recommendations was emphasised. The Garden Route case was seen as a reference point for strengthening oversight, especially on governance, public participation, and housing delivery.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41491/', 0),
    (41624, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-09-17', 'Human Settlements Q1 2025/26 Performance; Committee Strategic Plan; with Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to discuss the performance of the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) for the first quarter of 2025/26. The Minister reported that Programmes 1, 2 and 5 met their targets and said the Department would reassess Gauteng processes to identify blockages. She noted ongoing work to resolve title-deed backlogs, to phase out temporary residential units (TRUs) and to find permanent solutions for disaster-affected communities. The Director-General reported the Department achieved 84% (16 of 19) of planned targets in Q1. He highlighted good delivery in several programmes but noted underperformance in parts of the Informal Settlements and Rental Housing programmes due to evidence gaps and delayed reports. The CFO drew attention to year-end “hockey stick” spending patterns by municipalities. Committee members raised queries on title deed distributions, emergency accommodation and the Department’s advertising spend, and requested further detail on monitoring templates, provincial performance (notably Gauteng) and overspending on blocked projects.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41624/', 0),
    (41707, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-10-08', 'Human Settlements Portfolio Audit Outcomes; DHS, NHBRC, SHRA & NHFC 2024/25 Annual Reports (with Minister)', 'Video Annual Reports 2024/25 The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met virtually to receive a consolidated briefing from the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA), the Department of Human Settlements (DHS), and its entities on the 2024/25 audit and performance outcomes. The meeting provided an overview of audit results, departmental performance, and the operational status of entities, and allowed Members to engage on systemic challenges and proposed corrective measures. The Minister of Human Settlements noted that the Chairperson had raised many of the issues that were also of concern to the Department, including the financial sustainability of the PPRA and the Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS), as well as the ongoing review of the financial model for the Housing Development Agency (HDA). She stated that discussions between the Department and the Office of the AGSA were constructive and consistent, and that she had personally learned a great deal from the AGSA’s team regarding previous audits and areas of improvement within the Department and its entities. The AGSA reported a moderate improvement in audit outcomes across the human settlements sector. The Housing Development Agency (HDA) and the Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA) maintained clean audits, while the Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS) improved to an unqualified opinion. The DHS, National Home Builders Registration Council (NHBRC), and National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC) received unqualified audits with findings, whereas the Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA) remained qualified. Persistent challenges included material weaknesses in reporting and record-keeping, inconsistent performance verification, irregular expenditure amounting to R98 million, and delays in project completion. Underperformance in informal settlement upgrading, housing quality assurance, and title deed transfers was compounded by leadership vacancies and weak consequence management. The ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41707/', 0),
    (41728, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-10-09', 'Housing Development Agency (HDA), Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA), Community Schemes Ombud Services (CSOS) 2024/25 Annual Reports', 'Video 2024/25 Annual Reports The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to receive briefings from the Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA), the Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS), and the Housing Development Agency (HDA) on their 2024/25 audit and performance outcomes. The Committee’s oversight engagement focused on governance, financial accountability, and the implementation of transformation objectives across the human settlements sector. The Chairperson commended the HDA for achieving a clean audit outcome and for resolving all previous audit findings. He noted with concern that the PPRA remained the only entity with a qualified audit opinion, which was troubling given its central role in transformation within the property sector. Both the CSOS and HDA received unqualified audit opinions with findings, although operational and governance challenges remained. The PPRA reported an improved overall performance of 80%, compared to 66% in the previous year. Members expressed disappointment at the qualified audit outcome, recurring irregular expenditure, weak financial controls, and system failures affecting the processing of Fidelity Fund Certificates. Questions were raised about the Board’s oversight, the lack of tangible transformation outcomes, and the limited progress in resolving historical findings. The PPRA explained that most irregular expenditure was historical, dating back to 2017, and resulted from procedural lapses rather than fraud. Corrective measures included automation of manual systems, real-time monitoring, and strengthened consequence management to ensure accountability and operational improvement. The HDA presented a positive report confirming a clean audit and steady progress in strengthening governance and internal controls. The Agency achieved significant milestones in land acquisition, informal settlement upgrading, and asbestos roof removal, but fell short of its housing delivery target, completing 872 units out of 2 00', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41728/', 0),
    (41832, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-10-22', 'Emergency Housing; BRRR & Urban Land Justice Gathering Report; with Minister', 'Video Budgetary Review & Recommendations Reports BRRR The Minister gave opening remarks before having to leave. The National Department of Human Settlements (NDHS) explained the centralization of the Emergency Housing Response Fund to address underspending and political discrimination by provinces. There are significant challenges with temporary residential units (TRUs) including quality control, beneficiary verification, and prolonged stays. It explained disaster mitigation and preparedness efforts including geomapping, training of community leaders, and aligning plans with the National Disaster Management Centre as well as the devolution of responsibilities for minor and minimal disaster impacts to provinces and metros. The pilot project in Eastern Cape will provide a 40 sqm permanent housing solution instead of TRUs. The Committee considered and proposed amendments to the 2025 Human Settlements Budgetary Review & Recommendations Report (BRRR) before adopted it. The Committee also considered and adopted its Report on its attendance at the Urban Land Justice Gathering workshop held by Ndifuna Ukwazi.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41832/', 0),
    (41900, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-10-29', 'Prevention of Illegal Eviction & Unlawful Occupation of Land A/ Bill response; Free State Department of Human Settlements on progress made with Committee recommendations; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to receive briefings from Parliament''s Constitutional and Legal Services Office (CLSO) on the Prevention of Illegal Eviction from and Unlawful Occupation of Land Amendment Bill, and from the Free State Department of Human Settlements on progress with implementing previous Committee recommendations, particularly relating to blocked projects, contractor performance, financial management, and the state of housing delivery in the province. The Deputy Minister of Human Settlements reaffirmed government’s commitment to restoring dignity through housing provision and access to basic services. She outlined key priorities for the sector, including spatial justice, housing quality and financial accountability, noting that the meeting served as a platform for accountability between Parliament and the Department. The CLSO presentation summarised public submissions on the PIE Amendment Bill, which seeks to strengthen legal mechanisms against unlawful land occupation. Members raised extensive concerns regarding the Bill’s potential to criminalise poverty, and its implications for municipalities tasked with providing alternative accommodation. They questioned whether the Bill aligned with constitutional principles and the White Paper on Human Settlements. They generally agreed that the Department of Human Settlements (DHS) was best positioned to lead the legislative process to ensure comprehensive consultation and coherence with national policy. The Free State DHS reported on implementation progress and challenges. The province had 627 blocked projects, with 129 planned for unblocking in the next financial year. The Department highlighted poor workmanship, incomplete infrastructure, and disputes with contractors as major barriers to delivery. Members expressed frustration with recurring issues of poor planning, underspending, and the persistence of asbestos-affected housing. They demanded strict consequence management, improve', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41900/', 0),
    (41974, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-11-05', 'George Building Collapse: stakeholder input (with DHS & DEL Ministers)', 'Video A joint sitting of the Portfolio Committees on Human Settlements and Public Works and Infrastructure was convened to assess progress on investigations into the George building collapse of 6 May 2024, which claimed 34 lives. The Committees expressed deep frustration that more than a year later, no one had been held accountable. They reiterated that “justice delayed was justice denied,” and emphasised the urgent need for the South African Police Service (SAPS) and the Department of Employment and Labour (DEL) to finalise outstanding reports. The SAPS delegation informed Parliament that the police investigation would be completed by the end of November, pending the DEL’s submission of its final Occupational Health and Safety (OHS) report. It stressed that the investigation was prosecution-led, to ensure a watertight case for the court. The SAPS also clarified publicly that they had never instructed the George Municipality to withhold the structural engineering report from Parliament -- they had only discouraged publication in the media while the matter remained under investigation. This contradicted claims by the George municipal manager, triggering strong criticism from Members, who viewed the municipality’s conduct as obstructive. Deputy Minister Sibiya highlighted the DEL’s investigation into employer compliance, noting that the Department had received 77 compensation claims, including 68 via the Compensation Fund, of which 28 were fatal and 40 injury-related. Critically, of these claimants, 53 were foreign nationals, and only one had a valid work permit -- which had expired. This raised serious concerns about illegal labour practices and exploitation in the construction industry. The Committees warned that employers who knowingly hired undocumented workers had to face consequences. The DEL also highlighted a national shortage of inspectors -- only about 2 000 -- which severely limited its capacity to enforce labour and safety laws. The Council for the Built E', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41974/', 0),
    (42041, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-11-12', 'DHS on the Forensic Audit and Investigation on Communicare Social Housing Properties', 'Video The main item on the agenda concerned mass evictions by Communicare in the Western Cape, raised by Ms M Dlamini (EFF), who requested clarification on property ownership, accreditation, audits and the halting of evictions. Ms Dlamini expressed concern about the confusion over whether Communicare’s properties were state-owned, funded through social housing, or privately held. She talked about the need for clarity regarding tenant lease agreements, ownership of properties transferred to subsidiary companies, and the status of historical funding. She emphasised the urgency of protecting vulnerable communities from court-ordered evictions and ensuring that any ongoing investigations and profiling are expedited. The Department of Human Settlements (DHS) explained that the government is legally obliged to comply with court rulings on evictions but maintains a responsibility to assist vulnerable individuals through alternative accommodation, provided eligibility criteria are met. The Department outlined a two-phase forensic investigation into Communicare’s property portfolio to determine legitimacy, ownership and historical state funding. Phase one has been completed, and phase two is underway, with a target completion of six months. The Western Cape Government (WCG) and Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA) clarified that only three Communicare projects (599 units) are officially registered as social housing, while older units operate under standard rental agreements. Complaints from tenants in private stock are handled by the Rental Housing Tribunal. Members raised concerns about delays in tenant profiling, ongoing evictions, historical injustices in property ownership, and the impact on elderly and vulnerable tenants. Recommendations included suspending all evictions until the forensic audit is complete, expediting tenant profiling to determine eligibility for housing programmes, and ensuring coordinated engagement between national, provincial and City authori', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42041/', 0),
    (42092, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-11-19', 'Blocked social housing projects around the country', 'Video The Department of Human Settlements (DHS) and the Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA) briefed the Committee on ten blocked or stalled social housing projects, and the measures proposed to resolve them. SHRA reported that all ten projects had been approved before the COVID-19 pandemic, and were now financially non-viable due to severe cost escalations, contractor liquidation, community disruptions, and the depreciation of the rand. Collectively, these blocked projects accounted for approximately 6 000 units, representing a significant portion of the pipeline and contributing to SHRA’s reduced performance in recent years. SHRA explained that some projects had delivered completed units, while others had stalled before construction. Proposed interventions included retrospective grant funding, additional debt or equity, curtailment of unit numbers, transferring projects to capable institutions under Regulation 13, and termination as a last resort. The entity emphasised that termination would place the R552 million already invested at risk, and involve lengthy recovery processes. A workshop would be held with the SHRA Council to finalise the qualification criteria for determining which projects should receive support. The Department highlighted weaknesses in project planning, approval processes, and oversight. It stressed that the sector faced persistent risks, including weak developer capacity, inadequate municipal support, and inconsistent compliance from social housing institutions (SHIs). The DHS also acknowledged that previous funding decisions had not adequately considered long-term viability, and that improved due diligence was required. Committee Members raised strong concerns about the scale of underperformance, the repetition of non-performing developers, weak consequence management, and the lack of accountability for stalled projects. They questioned why the same developers continued to receive approvals across provinces, despite poor performance. ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42092/', 0),
    (42107, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-11-21', 'UN Habitat in Africa Memorandum of Understanding', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements received a detailed briefing from the Department of Human Settlements on the establishment of a UN Habitat country office in South Africa. The presentation outlined a multi-year process, culminating in the office''s imminent launch, with the goal of leveraging international expertise to address domestic challenges in informal settlements, urban safety, and spatial planning. The Committee also formally adopted a report with recommendations from its oversight visit to the Ahmed Kathrada House in Green Point, Cape Town, focusing on halting evictions and developing a collaborative plan to address the residents'' challenges. Key points coming to the fore during the Committee discussion were: South Africa would host a fully-funded UN Habitat country office to leverage global expertise on informal settlements and urban development, with a total commitment of US $5 million over five years. Committee Members raised concerns about the office becoming a costly administrative burden with little community impact, and questioned the three-year delay in its establishment. The Department explained the delay was due to standard legal processes for international agreements, and emphasised that the office would provide cost-effective access to technical resources and accelerate housing delivery. The Committee adopted a report recommending the immediate suspension of all evictions at Ahmed Kathrada House, and called for a stakeholder meeting to find a resolution. It was agreed that the Committee would hold a workshop to better understand the UN Habitat agreement, and that it would meet with provinces to assess their disaster readiness for the upcoming rainy season.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42107/', 0),
    (42108, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-11-21', 'Briefing by SIU on the allegations by Housing Development Agency of inflating prices on land for housing projects in several provinces', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to receive a briefing from the Special Investigating Unit (SIU) on allegations by the Housing Development Agency (HDA) of inflating prices on land for housing projects in several provinces. The investigation also looked into eight provincial human settlements Departments. Mandated by a May 2025 Presidential Proclamation, it focuses on serious maladministration, specifically allegations of inflated land prices, improper "middleman" commissions, and the purchase of land that remains unused. During the briefing, Committee Members sought clarity on accountability, legal processes, investigation timelines, and the handling of allegations across provinces. Members asked who is responsible for laying criminal charges and whether SIU reports are publicly accessible. The SIU indicated that it does not lay charges; instead, evidence of criminal conduct is referred to the NPA, which works with the Hawks to prepare dockets, affidavits, and documentation, with SIU monitoring progress. Reports are submitted to the President and may be accessed by the public, with the SIU increasingly publishing high-interest reports directly. Members repeatedly raised concerns about accountability for officials implicated in misconduct, particularly those who have left the system, emphasising that civil, professional, and criminal consequences remain enforceable. Questions also focused on whistleblower protection, the reliability of HDA reports, delayed submissions, and the inclusion of additional provinces or municipalities if required. The SIU noted that investigations are allegation-driven, with KwaZulu-Natal included via specific municipalities and Limpopo excluded due to no allegations. They clarified that HDA report delays were due to internal processes and not obstruction. Repeated themes included the need for timely accountability, robust legal and procedural safeguards, protection of whistleblowers, transparency in reporting, and sys', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42108/', 0),
    (42142, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-11-26', 'Provincial Readiness for Floods and Disasters ahead of rainy seasons; DHS Emergency Fund (with Minister)', 'Video The Portfolio Committee meeting focused on provincial and national readiness for disasters during the rainy season, with particular emphasis on emergency housing interventions, coordination challenges, and long-term solutions. Throughout the session, Members expressed concern about recurring disasters, slow or uneven responses, and the need for stronger preventive strategies. Several Members highlighted that despite annual readiness plans, implementation failures continued to leave victims struggling for assistance long after disasters occurred. They stressed that many communities remained in danger zones year after year, particularly along riverbanks and floodplains, because of limited housing options and systemic failures by government structures. Members argued that the government should prioritise making suitable land available for proper housing to minimise repeated disaster exposure and save lives and public resources. Questions were raised about national and provincial coordination systems, the verification of affected beneficiaries, and compliance with emergency housing criteria to prevent temporary accommodation from becoming permanent. Members also asked why readiness plans did not explicitly incorporate climate-change considerations, despite worsening weather patterns, frequent flooding, and increased fires in certain regions. In response, national and provincial officials provided detailed explanations. They noted that national teams were guaranteed to be on the ground within 48 hours of a reported disaster, although beneficiary verification, done by municipalities, often caused delays. In some areas, municipalities struggled to provide suitable land for temporary residential units (TRUs), or the land available was unsafe for construction. Officials acknowledged that contractors sometimes failed to deliver TRUs, but emphasised that most projects progressed effectively. National Department of Human Settlements representatives also explained that peo', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42142/', 0),
    (42211, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2025-12-03', 'Provincial Readiness for Floods and Disasters ahead of rainy seasons; DHS Emergency Fund; with Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee convened for further briefings on the state of readiness of provinces to deal with floods and disasters ahead of the rainy and fire season. It was briefed by Department of Human Settlements (DHS) officials of the Eastern Cape, Free State, KwaZulu-Natal and Western Cape, having received briefings from the five other provinces on their state of readiness in the previous week. The Committee concluded that the provinces were ready to deal with potential disasters that might occur over the holiday period. Suggestions were made for closer collaboration with the South African Weather Service for guidance, and to improve their planning process to ensure a more effective implementation of recovery interventions. The Committee was in agreement that the provision of transitional residential units (TRUs) was not an effective solution. The solution proposed by the Eastern Cape DHS to replace TRUs with the construction of permanent structures based on innovative sustainable building technology (ISBT) was embraced by the other provinces present at this meeting. This approach would considerably shorten the construction time and reduce wastage in terms of eliminating the repeated replacement of structures in disaster-prone areas. To fund this innovative intervention, the Eastern Cape DHS proposed that the Human Settlements Development Grant (HSDG) and the Disaster Relief Grant (DRF) be combined as a financing mechanism. The Committee resolved that the proposals deserved serious consideration.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42211/', 0),
    (42327, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2026-02-05', 'Communicare Social Housing on tenant profiling outcomes and resolutions on evictions and housing interventions; with the Minister and Deputy Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to receive a briefing from Communicare on tenant profiling, evictions, and the organisation’s housing programmes. Communicare''s Chief Executive Officer presented the organisation’s background, mandate and strategic direction. She emphasised Communicare’s role as a social enterprise providing affordable housing in Cape Town, managing over 3 400 rental units, and delivering social development programmes through its Vulamathuba arm. She outlined the challenges posed by intentional rental boycotts since 2018, resulting in R35 million in annual bad debts, and explained the organisation’s reliance on rental income to sustain operations and fund new developments. She highlighted ongoing forensic investigations into Communicare’s properties, noting delays since 2020, and appealed for urgency and clarity. She also addressed specific cases, including the Vredendal property, where structural concerns required redevelopment, but court rulings had postponed evictions pending investigation outcomes. During the discussion, Members raised concerns about the prolonged investigation, the treatment of vulnerable tenants, and the balance between financial sustainability and social responsibility. They asked whether the Department had finalised its investigation and requested binding timelines, as well as clarity on the Ahmed Kathrada building matter and interim protections for vulnerable households. They criticised Communicare’s eviction practices, particularly against elderly tenants and households with minors, and called for a moratorium on evictions until the investigation was concluded. The organisation’s prioritisation of commercial developments while vulnerable tenants faced eviction was also questioned. They queried the identity and cost of the investigator, raised concerns about inflated rental prices in Cape Town, criticised the lack of progress on resolutions from 2022, and called for regulation of rental costs and accoun', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42327/', 0),
    (42399, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2026-02-18', 'MAWIGA Petition; Breede Valley Petition; Slovo Park Petition Updates; with Ministry', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements met to receive progress reports on the MAWIGA (Mabopane/Ga-Rankuwa) petitions and the upgrading of Slovo Park Informal Settlement. The meeting focused on assessing progress made following the Committee’s previous oversight engagements, particularly regarding outstanding housing allocations, title deeds, intergovernmental coordination, and implementation of upgrading commitments under the Upgrading of Informal Settlements Programme (UISP). Progress updates on the petitions highlighted steps taken toward construction, land allocation, township establishment, and transfer processes, while also outlining administrative and technical delays affecting certain cases. Updates were also provided on infrastructure interventions in Slovo Park, including road grading, installation of CCTV infrastructure, procurement processes for water and sanitation services, and progress toward township formalisation. During the discussions, Members of the Portfolio Committee raised concerns about recurring delays, lack of firm and enforceable timelines, and weaknesses in intergovernmental coordination between national, provincial, and municipal departments. Members emphasised the need for consequence management where commitments to Parliament were not met and called for a consolidated, time-bound action plan with clear deliverables and accountability measures. Concerns were also raised about relocation plans for Slovo Park residents, the adequacy of community consultation, and the discrepancy between the number of households enumerated and the number that could be accommodated in the approved layout. Community representatives from Slovo Park acknowledged certain improvements but expressed frustration about slow implementation, flooding caused by incomplete roadworks, sanitation challenges, and uncertainty regarding relocation to the Southern Farms Development. They stressed the importance of meaningful engagement and adherence to previously ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42399/', 0),
    (42451, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2026-02-25', 'Progress made on acquired, abandoned and hijacked buildings; Plans to deal with blocked projects; NHFC governance, financial oversight, and related matters; with Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements (National Assembly) met for a briefing by the - Department of Human Settlements (DHS) and the Housing Development Agency (HDA) on the acquired abandoned and hijacked buildings - Department of Human Settlements and the Social Housing Regulatory Authority (SHRA) on plans to deal with blocked projects; and - National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC) on governance and oversight as well as reasons for suspension of the Chief Executive Officer (CEO). Ms Thembi Simelane, Minister of Human Settlements, said the meeting was in response to the many questions posed by the Committee in a previous meeting. The issues were mostly around governance and administration within the entities under the DHS. In particular, these entities were to provide clear details on their programmes to enhance service delivery. She told the Members that the maladministration within entities was being investigated. The HDA presented a progress report on the five buildings they have acquired. They had no blocked projects. Their objective was to use human settlements to regenerate inner cities. Funding remained a challenge. The NHFC made a detailed presentation on serious governance failures and the attempt by the newly installed board to turn the entity around. They provided more details on the investigations into more than 30 counts of alleged corruption and financial mismanagement. The NHFC also provided detailed explanation of the reasons for the suspension of executives. They provided extensive details on their loan book and how they plan to increase their pipeline. The SHRA were going to present on blocked projects and recovery plans to unblock them. However, due to reports being late or missing, the Committee deemed it necessary to excuse them from the meeting because it would have been unfair on the Minister or the Members to participate meaningfully. The Members appreciated the detailed plans and wanted more details on actual progress. They a', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42451/', 0),
    (42584, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2026-03-11', 'Briefings by eThekwini, KZN and North West on progress made on recommendations made by the Committee during oversight; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements received progress updates from when the Portfolio Committee undertook oversight visits to KwaZulu – Natal and North West Department of Human Settlements. Additionally, the Committee received a progress update from the eThekwini Municipality. The presentations highlighted progress in informal settlement upgrading, housing projects such as Banana City and Umbhayi and interventions to address flood–affected households. Members of the Portfolio Committee raised concerns regarding blocked housing projects, delays caused by insufficient bulk infrastructure, sanitation solutions, informal settlement upgrading strategies and the relocation of flood victims. The KwaZulu – Natal Department of Human Settlements reported that efforts were underway to unblock several stalled projects, strengthen due diligence processes with municipalities and ensure that bulk infrastructure was confirmed before housing projects commenced. Progress was also reported in relocating flood victims to permanent housing developments, including projects in Cornubia, Illovo and Pietermaritzburg. Members further discussed the need to scale up incremental upgrading in informal settlements, explore alternative sanitation technologies, address infrastructure constraints in rural areas and improve coordination between different spheres of government. The Deputy Minister of Human Settlements emphasised the importance of strengthening intergovernmental coordination, addressing blocked projects, and ensuring that housing delivery was aligned with infrastructure planning. She also highlighted the importance of programmes such as the Military Veterans Housing Programme. The meeting concluded with the Portfolio Committee commending progress made while emphasising the need for continued oversight to ensure that housing delivery challenges, infrastructure constraints and project delays were effectively addressed.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42584/', 0),
    (42603, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2026-03-13', 'CGE Report on the Experiences of Women Farm Workers', 'Video Commission for Gender Equality on the Report – Do women reap what they sow? The experiences of women farm workers, a sequel 2025 The Committee received a briefing from the Commission for Gender Equality (CGE) on its report examining the experiences of women farm workers in selected provinces. The Commission explained that the study had identified serious concerns regarding living and working conditions, including overcrowded accommodation, limited access to basic services, unequal wages, gender-based violence, and barriers to healthcare and land ownership. Members expressed concern about the persistent exploitation and vulnerability of women farm workers despite progressive labour and tenure legislation, noting the gap between policy commitments and the realities experienced in rural communities. Questions were raised regarding enforcement of labour and housing laws, inspections conducted on farms, the recruitment of foreign workers, and the need for improved coordination among government departments to address housing, labour rights and service delivery challenges. In response, the Commission indicated that although legislative improvements had been made, implementation remained weak in rural areas due to limited enforcement capacity and inadequate inspections. It noted that data and reporting mechanisms required improvement to better track labour violations and outcomes for farm workers. The Commission further highlighted ongoing engagements with relevant departments, academic institutions and oversight bodies to address identified gaps, including issues related to land allocation, labour protection and the exploitation of migrant workers. The Department of Human Settlements indicated its willingness to collaborate with the Commission and the Committee, noting that rural and farm worker housing programmes were already in place and that women were prioritised beneficiaries within these initiatives. The Committee welcomed the information provided and requested', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42603/', 0),
    (42654, 'Human Settlements', 291, '2026-03-18', 'Briefing by DHS, NHFC, PPRA, CSOS and HDA on the implementation of audit action plans for the 2024/25 financial year', 'Video In a virtual meeting, the Portfolio Committee on Human Settlements received briefings from the Department of Human Settlements and four of its entities, the National Housing Finance Corporation (NHFC), Property Practitioners Regulatory Authority (PPRA), Community Schemes Ombud Service (CSOS) and Housing Development Agency (HDA), on the implementation of its audit action plans for the 2024/25 financial year. The Chairperson opened the meeting by noting that while there was improvement in financial compliance, the Department faced systemic operational challenges. Irregular expenditure had climbed to R98 million, primarily driven by NHFC, and 83% of 24 human settlement projects were delayed. NHFC’s significant expenditure, high rate of project delays and lack of evidentiary support for reported performance claims demonstrated that positive financial compliance trends had not translated into effective service delivery. The Department reported that out of the 21 audit findings received, five were addressed and one remained at 0% progress. Regarding human resource management, the micro-organisational structure would be presented to the Minister and Top Management Committee for approval. The Audit Committee was appointed but its Charter still needed to be adopted. The inadequate controls related to the interface between the Housing Subsidy System and the Basic Accounting System were overseen by a newly appointed Chief Information Officer, and a systems analysis had been logged to address the design limitations. NHFC reported that it had received 37 audit findings of which 11 were resolved and two remained unresolved. The Abahlali Housing Association was placed under liquidation and the process of recovering R36 million was underway. The entity’s turnaround strategy included the separation of the credit lending division from the collections division as well as the recruitment of senior executives. PPRA reported that the appointment of its new Chief Financial Officer h', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42654/', 0)
